WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.920
[Amit Varma]: So you've clicked play on this podcast and you notice that hey, this episode is over

00:00:10.920 --> 00:00:12.400
[Amit Varma]: five and a half hours long.

00:00:12.400 --> 00:00:13.400
[Amit Varma]: What's going on?

00:00:13.400 --> 00:00:15.000
[Amit Varma]: Why does it need to be so long?

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:18.640
[Amit Varma]: People who discover this podcast for the first time often ask this question, though if they

00:00:18.640 --> 00:00:22.400
[Amit Varma]: become regular listeners, they ask, why couldn't it have been longer?

00:00:22.400 --> 00:00:25.600
[Amit Varma]: I wrote a post about this subject and I'll link it from the show notes.

00:00:25.600 --> 00:00:28.320
[Amit Varma]: But let me talk about one aspect of it for now.

00:00:28.320 --> 00:00:31.440
[Amit Varma]: When I started the show, it was about ideas and analysis.

00:00:31.440 --> 00:00:35.480
[Amit Varma]: The name of this podcast, The Seen and the Unseen, was inspired by Frederic Barcia's

00:00:35.480 --> 00:00:39.280
[Amit Varma]: 19th century essay, That Which is Seen and That Which is Not Seen.

00:00:39.280 --> 00:00:43.920
[Amit Varma]: The show, like the essay it was inspired from, was supposed to be about the unintended consequences

00:00:43.920 --> 00:00:45.340
[Amit Varma]: of public policy.

00:00:45.340 --> 00:00:46.380
[Amit Varma]: But then it evolved.

00:00:46.380 --> 00:00:51.500
[Amit Varma]: And over the last few years, the focus has shifted from ideas to people, from interviews

00:00:51.500 --> 00:00:52.500
[Amit Varma]: to conversations.

00:00:52.500 --> 00:00:56.620
[Amit Varma]: Initially, I'd get an expert on a subject and talk about the subject.

00:00:56.620 --> 00:00:59.320
[Amit Varma]: But those are dime a dozen on YouTube and other podcasts.

00:00:59.320 --> 00:01:04.080
[Amit Varma]: I gradually stepped back and began speaking about my guests' life and influences.

00:01:04.080 --> 00:01:08.480
[Amit Varma]: And in recent times, some of the longer episodes are oral histories, or you could even call

00:01:08.480 --> 00:01:10.200
[Amit Varma]: them assisted self portraits.

00:01:10.200 --> 00:01:14.460
[Amit Varma]: When you speak to someone about the life over a span of decades, you not only understand

00:01:14.460 --> 00:01:19.120
[Amit Varma]: them better, but you also get glimpses of the changing world as it turns and burns.

00:01:19.120 --> 00:01:23.140
[Amit Varma]: I love that aspect of the show, being able to live someone's life as seen in flashback

00:01:23.140 --> 00:01:24.640
[Amit Varma]: and self reflection.

00:01:24.640 --> 00:01:27.800
[Amit Varma]: Being able to unpeel layers of this complex world we live in.

00:01:27.800 --> 00:01:31.720
[Amit Varma]: And going by the love I get from all of you, it's clear that many, many people want that

00:01:31.720 --> 00:01:34.360
[Amit Varma]: kind of deep discursive conversation as well.

00:01:34.360 --> 00:01:38.440
[Amit Varma]: So if you're new to this, and you start listening and think, hey, get to the point, well, there

00:01:38.440 --> 00:01:39.440
[Amit Varma]: is no point.

00:01:39.440 --> 00:01:40.440
[Amit Varma]: That is the point.

00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:43.600
[Amit Varma]: I'll end this intro by saying thank you again to all the guests who've ever been on this

00:01:43.600 --> 00:01:48.520
[Amit Varma]: show and have trusted me enough to set aside their filters and open themselves up to me.

00:01:48.520 --> 00:02:07.160
[Unknown]: It's been a privilege and it's changed me as a person.

00:02:07.160 --> 00:02:08.640
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:02:08.640 --> 00:02:11.520
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is my old and dear friend Nilanjana Roy.

00:02:11.520 --> 00:02:16.320
[Amit Varma]: I first met Nilanjana in my blogging days, maybe 18 or 19 years ago, when she was already

00:02:16.320 --> 00:02:20.000
[Amit Varma]: one of the most highly regarded book critics in the country, and even in the world as her

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:21.720
[Amit Varma]: fame grew through the interwebs.

00:02:21.720 --> 00:02:24.200
[Amit Varma]: She wrote one of the longest running book columns in the world.

00:02:24.200 --> 00:02:27.520
[Amit Varma]: I think it appeared in the business standard for over two decades.

00:02:27.520 --> 00:02:29.840
[Amit Varma]: She's now a columnist for the Financial Times.

00:02:29.840 --> 00:02:32.000
[Amit Varma]: She's edited various compilations.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:35.280
[Amit Varma]: She's written two fabulous books of fantasy called The Wildings and The Hundred Names

00:02:35.280 --> 00:02:36.280
[Amit Varma]: of Darkness.

00:02:36.280 --> 00:02:40.200
[Amit Varma]: Her first literary novel for adults Black River is due out soon.

00:02:40.200 --> 00:02:41.440
[Amit Varma]: That's a biography.

00:02:41.440 --> 00:02:42.960
[Amit Varma]: What can I tell you about her?

00:02:42.960 --> 00:02:47.160
[Amit Varma]: Well, one of the things that I admire about Nilanjana is what a good reader she is.

00:02:47.160 --> 00:02:48.220
[Amit Varma]: She reads a lot.

00:02:48.220 --> 00:02:49.260
[Amit Varma]: She reads well.

00:02:49.260 --> 00:02:50.840
[Amit Varma]: She reads with intention.

00:02:50.840 --> 00:02:55.000
[Amit Varma]: Her reading deepens her sense of self and informs how she looks at the world and writes

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:56.000
[Amit Varma]: about it.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:58.240
[Amit Varma]: This is something I've always wanted to learn from her.

00:02:58.240 --> 00:03:02.800
[Amit Varma]: Some of this love for reading and books comes out through her superb collection of essays,

00:03:02.800 --> 00:03:03.800
[Amit Varma]: The Girl Who Ate Books.

00:03:03.800 --> 00:03:08.000
[Amit Varma]: I'll refer to that and quote from that during this conversation, where we spoke about reading,

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:13.080
[Amit Varma]: yes, but also about feminism, family, freedom and about these times we live in.

00:03:13.080 --> 00:03:16.080
[Amit Varma]: Before we get to it, though, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:03:16.080 --> 00:03:17.080
[Amit Varma]: And guess what?

00:03:17.080 --> 00:03:18.760
[Amit Varma]: The commercial is also about reading.

00:03:18.760 --> 00:03:20.880
[Amit Varma]: Use my code and subscribe to CTQ.

00:03:20.880 --> 00:03:24.480
[Amit Varma]: Do you want to read more?

00:03:24.480 --> 00:03:28.420
[Amit Varma]: I've put in a lot of work in recent years in building a reading habit.

00:03:28.420 --> 00:03:32.560
[Amit Varma]: This means that I read more books, but I also read more long form articles and essays.

00:03:32.560 --> 00:03:35.520
[Amit Varma]: There's a world of knowledge available through the internet.

00:03:35.520 --> 00:03:39.080
[Amit Varma]: But the problem we all face is, how do we navigate this knowledge?

00:03:39.080 --> 00:03:40.600
[Amit Varma]: How do we know what to read?

