[Amit Varma]: Uplevel yourself.

00:05:02.080 --> 00:05:21.360
[Amit Varma]: Thank you

00:05:21.360 --> 00:05:25.840
[Amit Varma]: So I'm glad we're finally getting to do this because I think I've been sort of asking you

00:05:25.840 --> 00:05:30.760
[Amit Varma]: for a while and you've been busy writing your books but finally here we are.

00:05:30.760 --> 00:05:36.400
[Guest]: I have to apologize for that it's just been a couple of years the last three years I think

00:05:36.400 --> 00:05:43.080
[Guest]: has been pretty full on both with the writing and then personal loss and for a while I don't

00:05:43.080 --> 00:05:50.600
[Guest]: think I was in a space where I wanted to speak as much as I wanted to listen and your podcast

00:05:50.600 --> 00:05:53.200
[Guest]: was a great comfort in that time.

00:05:53.200 --> 00:05:59.680
[Guest]: We have so few shows that actually give people a little time to you know sprawl.

00:05:59.680 --> 00:06:03.600
[Guest]: Usually you have your eye on the clock with the conversation and you're thinking 20 minutes,

00:06:03.600 --> 00:06:06.680
[Guest]: four questions, 45 minutes so much.

00:06:06.680 --> 00:06:08.680
[Guest]: You see what I mean?

00:06:08.680 --> 00:06:14.680
[Guest]: And I'm going to try very hard not to be going to interviewer mode though the questions that

00:06:14.680 --> 00:06:20.320
[Guest]: I wanted to ask you were things like you know why why did you decide that we needed this

00:06:20.320 --> 00:06:26.040
[Guest]: the sprawl of time, the slowness, this getting into things, spending a fair amount of an

00:06:26.040 --> 00:06:29.120
[Guest]: afternoon or a morning or an evening with your guests.

00:06:29.120 --> 00:06:33.320
[Guest]: I've enjoyed it as a listener.

00:06:33.320 --> 00:06:38.120
[Amit Varma]: In a very sleek way and a very slinky way you turn the tables on me but yeah to get

00:06:38.120 --> 00:06:41.160
[Amit Varma]: you warmed up yeah sure this is a conversation.

00:06:41.160 --> 00:06:46.840
[Amit Varma]: It sort of evolved that way in the sense that initially my sense was that you know people

00:06:46.840 --> 00:06:51.040
[Amit Varma]: have short attention spans a 20 minute podcast is perfect you got to grab them in the first

00:06:51.040 --> 00:06:57.280
[Amit Varma]: few seconds all of those things and I realized I was wrong for three reasons which I've sort

00:06:57.280 --> 00:07:01.600
[Amit Varma]: of spoken about and written about so much in the past that it'll be a repetition for

00:07:01.600 --> 00:07:06.520
[Amit Varma]: many of my listeners but the reasons being that one people tend to listen when they are

00:07:06.520 --> 00:07:10.680
[Amit Varma]: a captive audience so people will listen to podcasts or audiobooks when they are either

00:07:10.680 --> 00:07:15.720
[Amit Varma]: commuting or working out or doing errands like washing dishes and so on.

00:07:15.720 --> 00:07:20.080
[Amit Varma]: So you know when you're watching a video on YouTube you can just go to another tab or

00:07:20.080 --> 00:07:22.880
[Amit Varma]: change the window or turn your head and talk to someone who's standing there pick up a

00:07:22.880 --> 00:07:27.220
[Amit Varma]: book from the table but if you're jogging you're jogging you're not going to start doing

00:07:27.220 --> 00:07:32.000
[Amit Varma]: something else so one you're a captive audience two people listen at higher speeds which is

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:38.540
[Amit Varma]: easy to do because our normal speaking speed is between 150 to 200 words a minute I speak

00:07:38.540 --> 00:07:44.080
[Amit Varma]: at about 160 because I'm a middle-aged man now I'm a little slow but our brain can comprehend

00:07:44.080 --> 00:07:50.700
[Amit Varma]: language at 500 words a minute so actually it's really easy to listen at higher speeds

00:07:50.700 --> 00:07:54.240
[Amit Varma]: and the way to do it is people might think oh it's squeaky and I'll miss nuances and

00:07:54.240 --> 00:07:59.160
[Amit Varma]: all of that actually you don't at all because your brain adjusts so if you take it to 1.2

00:07:59.160 --> 00:08:03.660
[Amit Varma]: wait for it to normalize take it to 1.5 so on and so forth like I can listen to stuff

00:08:03.660 --> 00:08:09.440
[Amit Varma]: between 2.5 to 3x and not lose any nuance not lose any pauses any gaps because the brain

00:08:09.440 --> 00:08:14.080
[Amit Varma]: just adjusts and processes them that way and the third important reason is that I think

00:08:14.080 --> 00:08:19.540
[Amit Varma]: in modern times people crave depth and the thing is it's not that there are two kinds

00:08:19.540 --> 00:08:23.600
[Amit Varma]: of people in the world and the one kind has short attention span one kind doesn't I think

00:08:23.600 --> 00:08:28.320
[Amit Varma]: everyone has a short attention span for a lot of the time so there might be times where

00:08:28.320 --> 00:08:32.480
[Amit Varma]: I am constantly distracted and looking at my smartphone and you can't really hold my

00:08:32.480 --> 00:08:37.760
[Amit Varma]: attention but there are also times where I want to sit down and go deep and media today

00:08:37.760 --> 00:08:43.140
[Amit Varma]: unfortunately because there's a race to the bottom it it's it's a mile wide and an inch

00:08:43.140 --> 00:08:48.120
[Amit Varma]: deep as our mutual friend Prem Panicker says so eloquently and people get that and people

00:08:48.120 --> 00:08:52.960
[Amit Varma]: crave depth and they value depth which I've discovered through the love I get from my

00:08:52.960 --> 00:08:58.800
[Amit Varma]: listeners and I think it's in a sense and this is a theme we'll surely talk about in

00:08:58.800 --> 00:09:04.860
[Amit Varma]: your context as well but I think just shifting forms not just changes the work that you do

00:09:04.860 --> 00:09:10.000
[Amit Varma]: but it also changes a person that you are it makes like for me I think I'm and I was

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:14.040
[Amit Varma]: discussing this in an episode I released I recorded yesterday with Pradeep magazine it'll

00:09:14.040 --> 00:09:20.600
[Amit Varma]: probably release after this but you know and where I was talking about how it's made me

00:09:20.600 --> 00:09:26.400
[Amit Varma]: less judgmental and more open to listening to people and getting involved in their stories

00:09:26.400 --> 00:09:30.240
[Amit Varma]: like you know Stephen Covey once said that we don't listen to understand we listen to

00:09:30.240 --> 00:09:35.400
[Amit Varma]: respond which is a really bad thing I mean to have a good conversation you have to kind

00:09:35.400 --> 00:09:39.520
[Amit Varma]: of put your ego out of it and just sit down and listen and I think doing this has taught

00:09:39.520 --> 00:09:45.120
[Amit Varma]: me to do that and Pradeep in different ways also shared how the last 10 years have made

00:09:45.120 --> 00:09:49.560
[Amit Varma]: him much less judgmental which reflects in this beautiful memoir that he's written called

00:09:49.560 --> 00:09:54.400
[Amit Varma]: not just cricket which is an episode that will come after this so people can hear that

00:09:54.400 --> 00:09:58.480
[Amit Varma]: and I've been reflecting about this as well I've been you know doing a fair bit of sort

00:09:58.480 --> 00:10:03.840
[Amit Varma]: of self-reflection on how the work that you do can change who you are and the work that

00:10:03.840 --> 00:10:10.480
[Amit Varma]: you do is shaped so much by the form and you have also worked across different forms in

00:10:10.480 --> 00:10:15.880
[Amit Varma]: your life done different kinds of reading different kinds of writing so you know although

00:10:15.880 --> 00:10:21.560
[Amit Varma]: this was not something I planned specifically to ask but what are your thoughts on this

00:10:21.560 --> 00:10:25.840
[Guest]: I'm picking up on some of the words that you've used because they are exactly what I wanted

00:10:25.840 --> 00:10:32.320
[Guest]: to talk about today it's that ache for depth it's not just a need for depth or a sense

00:10:32.320 --> 00:10:37.520
[Guest]: that we have that missing in our lives somewhere the more frantic that we get the more time

00:10:37.520 --> 00:10:43.000
[Guest]: we are spending on Twitter social media keeping up it's not just social media you know to

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:50.040
[Guest]: be honest the world makes you feel like you have to keep running to stand still and just

00:10:50.040 --> 00:10:55.740
[Guest]: just to be in the swim and whether it's news or whether it's your lives there's no emphasis

00:10:55.740 --> 00:11:02.400
[Guest]: on pausing you know there's just you're supposed to consume one experience after the other

00:11:02.400 --> 00:11:07.240
[Guest]: just the way that you consume the news and there's this constant frantic cry of next

00:11:07.240 --> 00:11:14.440
[Guest]: next next I've spent much to my surprise I think a lifetime of moving around a lot between

00:11:14.440 --> 00:11:21.400
[Guest]: jobs not settling to one kind of writing one kind of job but grounded fundamentally in

00:11:21.400 --> 00:11:27.640
[Guest]: reading and writing I don't think I intended that to happen but it's been if you think

00:11:27.640 --> 00:11:33.120
[Guest]: about it this way in this ocean that's constantly tugging you this way or that way my reading

00:11:33.120 --> 00:11:39.200
[Guest]: in different languages different bodies of work different kinds of things has been like

00:11:39.200 --> 00:11:44.480
[Guest]: a sheet anchor it's something that you can return to at any point of time in your life

00:11:44.480 --> 00:11:50.160
[Guest]: no matter how grievous the world around you is and your reading also challenges you at

00:11:50.160 --> 00:11:55.800
[Guest]: some point to seek a certain kind of depth you know that libraries have long been used

00:11:55.800 --> 00:12:02.320
[Guest]: as parallel schools or colleges in the depression American libraries became places where people

00:12:02.320 --> 00:12:07.360
[Guest]: taught themselves skills and they did that by reading 30 books and on the subject and

00:12:07.360 --> 00:12:13.240
[Guest]: they found their subject basically by walking into this huge cathedral of books practically

00:12:13.240 --> 00:12:19.740
[Guest]: and asking themselves a simple question what am I curious about what am I interested in

00:12:19.740 --> 00:12:24.280
[Guest]: the other thing that you've touched about the fact that your work changes you I get

00:12:24.280 --> 00:12:31.600
[Guest]: asked so often about writing by people who see it as who used to see it at least as a

00:12:31.600 --> 00:12:38.640
[Guest]: pathway to a certain kind of success or celebrity or stability and they really want to have

00:12:38.640 --> 00:12:44.800
[Guest]: written their books and each time I want to I really want to beg them to sit down and

00:12:44.800 --> 00:12:49.960
[Guest]: enjoy the writing itself you know to sit there quietly with the page and with whatever you're

00:12:49.960 --> 00:12:55.840
[Guest]: working on and to discover yourself as a writer or discover yourself as a reader as well for

00:12:55.840 --> 00:13:02.040
[Guest]: me what am I doing these days I've just finished a novel Black River which is probably the

00:13:02.040 --> 00:13:07.880
[Guest]: first novel I've written for an entirely adult audience my two books before that the Wildings

00:13:07.880 --> 00:13:13.500
[Guest]: and the Hundred Names of Darkness well could go either way my youngest reader was six years

00:13:13.500 --> 00:13:21.720
[Guest]: old and my oldest reader was 92 years old a Spanish biker you know who sent me pictures

00:13:21.720 --> 00:13:27.720
[Guest]: of himself with his two cats beautiful yeah that is the joy of being a writer actually

00:13:27.720 --> 00:13:33.800
[Guest]: you never know who you're going to reach and if you're in a rush to get to some page three

00:13:33.800 --> 00:13:39.600
[Guest]: success or to get on to the TV shows or to be invited to the Jaipur Literature Festival

00:13:39.600 --> 00:13:46.280
[Guest]: as fun as all those things are that's not what the work is about you know and I want

00:13:46.280 --> 00:13:52.000
[Guest]: to tell people to to learn to take their time with whatever it is that they're doing whether

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:56.400
[Guest]: it's with a book or with an author the pleasure of immersion that's the word that we are looking

00:13:56.400 --> 00:14:01.400
[Guest]: for really you know immersion is difficult because everything else in our modern life

00:14:01.400 --> 00:14:05.920
[Guest]: mitigates against it it says that when you've reached a place you need to rush to reach

00:14:05.920 --> 00:14:11.080
[Guest]: the other place if you've traveled to so many countries you need to go somewhere else and

00:14:11.080 --> 00:14:15.720
[Guest]: yet it's only by standing still and holding on whatever it is that I admire in my life

00:14:15.720 --> 00:14:22.500
[Guest]: whether it's specific writers specific books or whether it's the freedom struggle you know

00:14:22.500 --> 00:14:29.040
[Guest]: I'm struck by how much Nehru, Gandhi, Dr. B.R. Ambedkar, Sarojini Naidu, Aruna Asif Ali

00:14:29.040 --> 00:14:35.800
[Guest]: all of them how much time they actually spent thinking about what went into a national movement

00:14:35.800 --> 00:14:41.080
[Guest]: and trying to visualize independence Gloria Steinem I'm jumping like crazy so you'll have

00:14:41.080 --> 00:14:47.040
[Guest]: to call me back at some point but Gloria Steinem says that one of the tasks ahead of us is

00:14:47.040 --> 00:14:52.120
[Guest]: how to imagine a new world and she doesn't say you know how to bring that new world into

00:14:52.120 --> 00:14:57.780
[Guest]: being that's a later task or whatever but truly if you cannot imagine a better reality

00:14:57.780 --> 00:15:03.400
[Guest]: a better life then how you're going to reach that and you're not going to be able to get

00:15:03.400 --> 00:15:08.840
[Guest]: to that point if you're constantly racing from one action to another it's not just about

00:15:08.840 --> 00:15:14.520
[Guest]: slowing down it's about what you're slowing down for right so when you get back to your

00:15:14.520 --> 00:15:20.880
[Guest]: early experiences of reading often we rush into what was your first book but most people's

00:15:20.880 --> 00:15:26.660
[Guest]: early experiences of reading are actually of being told a story you know of listening

00:15:26.660 --> 00:15:32.480
[Guest]: when you're very very small very young and that is the ultimate slowness because you're

00:15:32.480 --> 00:15:38.480
[Guest]: sitting there you're quiet but you're not passive you're taking in something and you're

00:15:38.480 --> 00:15:43.960
[Guest]: learning to imagine for the first time in your very very young life this world that

00:15:43.960 --> 00:15:50.640
[Guest]: doesn't actually exist before your eyes I've looked at that and I think one of the big

00:15:50.640 --> 00:15:56.120
[Guest]: themes that I keep coming back to is why in all these centuries do we keep reaching for

00:15:56.120 --> 00:16:02.680
[Guest]: story why do we keep reaching for myths why is it that pretty much from the dawn of humanity

00:16:02.680 --> 00:16:08.120
[Guest]: one of the first things we do is not just live in the world but we reach for stories

00:16:08.120 --> 00:16:12.920
[Guest]: to try and explain what kind of world it is that we live in you know the oldest books

00:16:12.920 --> 00:16:18.820
[Guest]: and the oldest tales go back to the dawn of humanity itself and I find that incredibly

00:16:18.820 --> 00:16:25.200
[Guest]: moving and slightly surreal that we can sit here so many centuries later and still fully

00:16:25.200 --> 00:16:29.680
[Guest]: understand and be moved by something like the epic of Gilgamesh you know which was the

00:16:29.680 --> 00:16:34.920
[Guest]: first written epic or we can relate to the Mahabharata and the Ramayana whatever your

00:16:34.920 --> 00:16:39.440
[Guest]: own epics are we can relate to them as though they were written yesterday you know it's

00:16:39.440 --> 00:16:46.320
[Guest]: that universal people just reach across the centuries all the time with writing so a number

00:16:46.320 --> 00:16:52.480
[Amit Varma]: of things I want to kind of double click on and kind of go a little deeper and one of

00:16:52.480 --> 00:16:57.960
[Amit Varma]: them comes from two of the things that you mentioned just now one is of course how you

00:16:57.960 --> 00:17:02.440
[Amit Varma]: know that Therav has gone from our lives where we can just sit and think about stuff and

00:17:02.440 --> 00:17:07.360
[Amit Varma]: not just go from sensation to sensation and so on and so forth and the other is what you

00:17:07.360 --> 00:17:13.600
[Amit Varma]: said about our freedom fighters having the time to you know to sit and think about stuff

00:17:13.600 --> 00:17:18.040
[Amit Varma]: you know Nehru writing all that he did in jail in such eloquent language without a library

00:17:18.040 --> 00:17:24.560
[Amit Varma]: available to him and so on and so forth one TIL moment I had about our modern times came

00:17:24.560 --> 00:17:29.440
[Amit Varma]: from Jonathan Haidt when he said that even though we have all of literature and all of

00:17:29.440 --> 00:17:35.000
[Amit Varma]: knowledge available to us at the click of a mouse most of what we are consuming was

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:40.700
[Amit Varma]: produced in the last three days right so we go from sensation to sensation to sensation

00:17:40.700 --> 00:17:46.600
[Amit Varma]: to sensation and that quietitude is not there like you know when you and I were growing

00:17:46.600 --> 00:17:50.960
[Amit Varma]: up we had a lot of me time and we had a lot of me time because there was no option there

00:17:50.960 --> 00:17:56.000
[Amit Varma]: weren't so many things to do you know we read a lot why did we read a lot because there

00:17:56.000 --> 00:18:01.720
[Amit Varma]: was so few books available to us that we read everything we could kind of grab hold of I

00:18:01.720 --> 00:18:06.640
[Amit Varma]: mean you and I were perhaps much more privileged and fortunate in this regard but for most

00:18:06.640 --> 00:18:11.720
[Amit Varma]: people and so many of my guests of our vintage you're just reading everything indiscriminately

00:18:11.720 --> 00:18:16.600
[Amit Varma]: that you can get hold of and you have the time to sit down and think and you know like

00:18:16.600 --> 00:18:22.680
[Amit Varma]: you said like I once wrote a column about you know that old lament about how did we

00:18:22.680 --> 00:18:29.440
[Amit Varma]: have such great leaders in the 20s 30s 40s even 50s and today the quality of politician

00:18:29.440 --> 00:18:36.160
[Amit Varma]: is what it is and my theory about that was that was an economic theory which is that

00:18:36.160 --> 00:18:40.680
[Amit Varma]: it boils down to incentives that the great freedom fighters all the people you named

00:18:40.680 --> 00:18:43.840
[Amit Varma]: you know there was no power at the end of the line for them so they weren't lusting

00:18:43.840 --> 00:18:49.760
[Amit Varma]: for power they were animated by higher principles and that calling attracted the kind of people

00:18:49.760 --> 00:18:53.560
[Amit Varma]: who were animated by higher principles and that's why you got all the people that you

00:18:53.560 --> 00:18:58.760
[Amit Varma]: did your Nehru, your Ambedkar, your Sarojini Naidu and so on and today it's you know people

00:18:58.760 --> 00:19:03.240
[Amit Varma]: are not attracted to politics for that reason for higher principles they are attracted for

00:19:03.240 --> 00:19:09.160
[Amit Varma]: the lust for power and money and so on but I think that the reason that you know if I

00:19:09.160 --> 00:19:13.560
[Amit Varma]: were to add a second reason to that I think what you just said is a great reason that

00:19:13.560 --> 00:19:20.040
[Amit Varma]: in an earlier generation you had the scope for quiet reflection even if you didn't have

00:19:20.040 --> 00:19:28.560
[Amit Varma]: all the libraries of the world sort of available to you and it strikes me that today to be

00:19:28.560 --> 00:19:35.680
[Amit Varma]: able to reflect in that way it has to be an act of will where an individual says I want

00:19:35.680 --> 00:19:40.440
[Amit Varma]: to put my smartphone away I want to put the laptop away I want to sit and reflect earlier

00:19:40.440 --> 00:19:43.960
[Amit Varma]: it was almost default that you reflect a lot of the time because what else is there to

00:19:43.960 --> 00:19:49.320
[Amit Varma]: do but now we are just going from sensation to sensation picking picking up our smartphones

00:19:49.320 --> 00:19:54.440
[Amit Varma]: 20 times an hour you know chasing the dopamine hit of the latest notification or Facebook

00:19:54.440 --> 00:20:00.600
[Amit Varma]: like and for most people therefore you are just you're just kind of trapped in this what

00:20:00.600 --> 00:20:05.760
[Amit Varma]: are your sort of thoughts on this have you found yourself fighting it yourself like I

00:20:05.760 --> 00:20:11.120
[Amit Varma]: have you know have you found yourself fighting it yourself and is this something therefore

00:20:11.120 --> 00:20:15.600
[Amit Varma]: that you would lament like I think we would both agree that it's almost miraculous and

00:20:15.600 --> 00:20:20.880
[Amit Varma]: magical that so much knowledge is available to us at the click of a mouse but this is

00:20:20.880 --> 00:20:26.240
[Guest]: a downside so what are your sort of thoughts I'm very of nostalgia I think we all are because

00:20:26.240 --> 00:20:33.960
[Guest]: we tend to put an Instagram filter on the past to some extent but when I look back at

00:20:33.960 --> 00:20:41.780
[Guest]: my childhood the kind of childhoods that many of us had it seems impossibly idyllic because

00:20:41.780 --> 00:20:48.480
[Guest]: it was uncluttered I think there was extraordinary privilege for me not just in terms of caste

00:20:48.480 --> 00:20:55.000
[Guest]: majority religion coming from a reasonably affluent background but there was extraordinary

00:20:55.000 --> 00:21:01.740
[Guest]: privilege for me in the incredible luck of being born into a family where books art music

00:21:01.740 --> 00:21:06.960
[Guest]: and all of that were prized they were not coveted they were not collected they were

00:21:06.960 --> 00:21:14.600
[Guest]: just seen as these wondrous things that made your everyday duty-bound ritualistic life

00:21:14.600 --> 00:21:21.800
[Guest]: that much more not just enjoyable but it you know reaching for whatever it was that you

00:21:21.800 --> 00:21:27.480
[Guest]: were reaching for a ballet performance in Delhi, Spik Mckay concerts, your own culture

00:21:27.480 --> 00:21:32.680
[Guest]: in Bengali whatever it was it was understood that this added a layer of deep meaning to

00:21:32.680 --> 00:21:38.480
[Guest]: life and I think I was very fortunate to grow up in two households one in Calcutta one in

00:21:38.480 --> 00:21:44.120
[Guest]: Delhi where we were surrounded with books because people would rather collect them than

00:21:44.120 --> 00:21:51.760
[Guest]: refurbish the furniture I took that for granted but let me describe what a Delhi childhood

00:21:51.760 --> 00:21:59.920
[Guest]: was like at that time this was in a key part of the 1970s and mothers used to by and large

00:21:59.920 --> 00:22:04.520
[Guest]: it was a time when women were just starting to work outside the home so unfortunately

00:22:04.520 --> 00:22:09.320
[Guest]: most of these were mothers and mothers used to turn their children out of the house after

00:22:09.320 --> 00:22:16.080
[Guest]: school like puppies you know to play in open spaces and used to roam fearlessly through

00:22:16.080 --> 00:22:21.360
[Guest]: many of your neighborhoods and this went across class by the way this was true for small

00:22:21.360 --> 00:22:25.960
[Guest]: mohalla neighborhoods in model town and this was true for government colonies like Chanakya

00:22:25.960 --> 00:22:31.840
[Guest]: Puri where I grew up or Lodhi colony or whatever there'd be somebody sitting out on a chaat

00:22:31.840 --> 00:22:38.000
[Guest]: by somewhere and you'd wander around in and out of each other's houses and so the part

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:44.520
[Guest]: of it that was not bookish was balanced by a tremendous activity you know I climbed trees

00:22:44.520 --> 00:22:49.240
[Guest]: I fell out of them I climbed roofs I fell off them this this is by the way something

00:22:49.240 --> 00:22:54.560
[Guest]: of a running theme in my life and I think we thought nothing of running around a space

00:22:54.560 --> 00:23:01.440
[Guest]: that would have been easily 10 kilometers square you know we knew every quadrangle we

00:23:01.440 --> 00:23:07.880
[Guest]: dreamed of secret passages in Palam airfield which was nearby we knew which parts had jackals

00:23:07.880 --> 00:23:12.640
[Guest]: and were to be avoided and which parts were actually a little more friendly and there

00:23:12.640 --> 00:23:18.560
[Guest]: was a sugarcane stand in that field that we all avoided because the Cobras used to live

00:23:18.560 --> 00:23:24.320
[Guest]: there and we avoided it without fear you know the natural world the bookish world the outdoors

00:23:24.320 --> 00:23:30.000
[Guest]: world they all flowed into and through each other even when television came in which would

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:36.520
[Guest]: have been roughly the end of the 70s early 80s programs were screened in the evening

00:23:36.520 --> 00:23:43.880
[Guest]: and they were mind-numbingly boring to begin with yeah absolutely you know the old the

00:23:43.880 --> 00:23:48.640
[Guest]: golden age of television was a little further down the line when Buniyad and Humlog and

00:23:48.640 --> 00:23:57.200
[Guest]: all that good stuff happened so we lived a very active life not a passive life how do

00:23:57.200 --> 00:24:02.040
[Guest]: I struggle with this all the time I still find it difficult to avoid the stickiness

00:24:02.040 --> 00:24:07.760
[Guest]: of Twitter but I think I've grown better at just putting the phone off the phone is the

00:24:07.760 --> 00:24:13.400
[Guest]: biggest thing you know that anxiety of I'll miss out if I don't see a message right now

00:24:13.400 --> 00:24:18.400
[Guest]: and you have to train yourself to moving into it's fine it's fine to respond to something

00:24:18.400 --> 00:24:24.680
[Guest]: even three days later nothing is that urgent really you know except for okay editorial

00:24:24.680 --> 00:24:29.880
[Guest]: deadlines or something of the sort but even that you can train yourself to just check

00:24:29.880 --> 00:24:36.000
[Guest]: in with the phone once or twice a day and that opens up space for you to check in on

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:41.960
[Guest]: everything else you know otherwise we spend I think what we're pushing back against is

00:24:41.960 --> 00:24:47.480
[Guest]: something that was also not true of the early web you know you're enough of an 80s 90s I

00:24:47.480 --> 00:24:52.360
[Guest]: mean I think I just touched on what a childhood in the 1970s was like an Indian childhood

00:24:52.360 --> 00:24:58.200
[Guest]: was never fully idyllic but you know things like the emergency which happened when I was

00:24:58.200 --> 00:25:05.040
[Guest]: very very young 97 98 suddenly it seemed to you that the walls were speaking in admonitory

00:25:05.040 --> 00:25:11.680
[Guest]: tones or because children pick up hypocrisy very fast there were these bright breezy songs

00:25:11.680 --> 00:25:17.440
[Guest]: you know which means remove the garbage and somewhere in there an uneasy prickle which

00:25:17.440 --> 00:25:22.520
[Guest]: told you even as a child that something else was supposed to be cleaned up and removed

00:25:22.520 --> 00:25:26.960
[Guest]: and you weren't very comfortable with what that something was you didn't know that it

00:25:26.960 --> 00:25:35.320
[Guest]: was people and their homes that were being removed I was born in 1971 so somewhere you

00:25:35.320 --> 00:25:41.280
[Guest]: know we always valorize our own births and I think in my memory my birth goes hand in

00:25:41.280 --> 00:25:47.440
[Guest]: hand with the story of the Bangladesh war a time when Mrs. Gandhi was probably at the

00:25:47.440 --> 00:25:53.400
[Guest]: height of her popularity seen as this strong and immensely capable leader and it's something

00:25:53.400 --> 00:25:59.600
[Guest]: of a lesson to us that just five years later she took India into its first not last experiment

00:25:59.600 --> 00:26:06.720
[Guest]: with authoritarianism but as a child you know what you're processing all of this in as this

00:26:06.720 --> 00:26:15.160
[Guest]: duality of immense security which lasted right up to the Billa Ranga murder of those two

00:26:15.160 --> 00:26:21.560
[Guest]: the brother and sister Geeta and Sanjay and we so used now in a huge megalopolis which

00:26:21.560 --> 00:26:27.240
[Guest]: is what Delhi has become and Bombay has become that we forget what a shock something like

00:26:27.240 --> 00:26:33.640
[Guest]: that sends out you know the ripples of sadness and shared grief and collective mourning that

00:26:33.640 --> 00:26:40.560
[Guest]: happens when a city is a smaller more intimate space in the 1970s Delhi was still a collection

00:26:40.560 --> 00:26:48.720
[Guest]: of villages held together by a substrate of government colonies and you know vague optimism

00:26:48.720 --> 00:26:55.640
[Guest]: again in memory it's important to just keep looking back and looking back further because

00:26:55.640 --> 00:27:02.720
[Guest]: nostalgia is always cut through with its opposite right so 1947 which was India's independence

00:27:02.720 --> 00:27:09.760
[Guest]: was remembered by the generation after that in story and in memory it was a living memory

00:27:09.760 --> 00:27:14.960
[Guest]: but so was partition you know and early on I think one thing we learned about living

00:27:14.960 --> 00:27:20.040
[Guest]: in this country we knew that because of the years of the British Empire the rule of the

00:27:20.040 --> 00:27:26.440
[Guest]: British Empire we knew that we didn't live in the first world we lived in the third world

00:27:26.440 --> 00:27:30.440
[Guest]: we knew that empirically speaking we lived in a very poor country that was struggling

00:27:30.440 --> 00:27:36.920
[Guest]: to fill its treasuries again and I think for my generation some of the respect for the

00:27:36.920 --> 00:27:42.440
[Guest]: leaders we had right after independence comes from that space it's not so much what we think

00:27:42.440 --> 00:27:50.880
[Guest]: of today you know worship of a particular political party or allegiance the tribal thing

00:27:50.880 --> 00:27:56.220
[Guest]: it is more a genuine respect and wonder for the fact that India bucked what everybody

00:27:56.220 --> 00:28:01.680
[Guest]: expected of the country foreign correspondents expected India to fall apart in five years

00:28:01.680 --> 00:28:07.160
[Guest]: and then 10 years and 15 years and you know it seemed every decade that somebody was ringing

00:28:07.160 --> 00:28:15.480
[Guest]: the doom in the 1980s again Indira Gandhi's assassination the trouble in Punjab all of

00:28:15.480 --> 00:28:21.000
[Guest]: that the riots in Delhi everything is something that you live through you know you feel it

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:28.120
[Guest]: on your skin and through that what happens is that books become a way of understanding

00:28:28.120 --> 00:28:34.280
[Guest]: the far past recent history and also a comfort and a refuge I know I've traveled very far

00:28:34.280 --> 00:28:39.720
[Guest]: from where we expect it to be but you know maybe we keep circling back to this whole

00:28:39.720 --> 00:28:44.600
[Guest]: thing of reading and I just want to take a moment to say something that surprised me

00:28:44.600 --> 00:28:50.660
[Guest]: when I studied as in not studied but just read about the freedom struggle was how many

00:28:50.660 --> 00:28:58.320
[Guest]: of our leaders from Maulana Azad to Ramanohar Lohia to the ones we've just named set a great

00:28:58.320 --> 00:29:05.080
[Guest]: store by reading and building their own libraries and once I sat down for a column I was writing

00:29:05.080 --> 00:29:09.640
[Guest]: for the business standard which is the first place that opened its doors to me and gave

00:29:09.640 --> 00:29:16.520
[Guest]: me the space to be a columnist at the then you know ridiculously young age of 22-23 they

00:29:16.520 --> 00:29:23.760
[Guest]: really made me into a journalist but one of the columns I did for them was about the libraries

00:29:23.760 --> 00:29:29.000
[Guest]: of the leaders of the national movement and you start going through those books you know

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:36.920
[Guest]: 3,000 of them 4,000 of them Gandhi's collection Nehru's collection and you start to see that

00:29:36.920 --> 00:29:44.080
[Guest]: they use books to really read their way into the whole question of what is freedom and

00:29:44.080 --> 00:29:48.880
[Guest]: what is our independent country going to be and it's so fascinating that they reached

00:29:48.880 --> 00:29:56.640
[Guest]: all the way across you know Gandhi read American early vegetarians for inspiration along with

00:29:56.640 --> 00:30:01.280
[Guest]: stories about the Europe reformation and all of that and then they circled back to their

00:30:01.280 --> 00:30:08.160
[Guest]: own country their own language and come up with an extremely particular very Indian approach

00:30:08.160 --> 00:30:13.600
[Guest]: to democracy none of that is accidental you know I don't think there was a point of time

00:30:13.600 --> 00:30:18.160
[Guest]: at which they valorized reading in their own minds or they said this is a good thing to

00:30:18.160 --> 00:30:23.800
[Guest]: do or was self-conscious about it it's just that I find it so touching that the two things

00:30:23.800 --> 00:30:30.000
[Guest]: that they did all through the years of the freedom struggle from the 1900s onwards they

00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:35.320
[Guest]: wrote letters furiously you know our sense of the past really has to change we think

00:30:35.320 --> 00:30:40.360
[Guest]: that we so cool with our Twitter updates and our blog posts and everything but if you start

00:30:40.360 --> 00:30:48.240
[Guest]: to look at those gigantic volumes of correspondence you realize that even on his silent days Gandhi

00:30:48.240 --> 00:30:54.240
[Guest]: spent so much time you know composing these swift emails these notes to himself he spent

00:30:54.240 --> 00:31:01.760
[Guest]: a life in writing Saroji Naidu moving between the poems and the speeches where her auditory

00:31:01.760 --> 00:31:08.000
[Guest]: which today seems to us to be a little flowery and a little overblown for that time though

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:13.720
[Guest]: it was deep with emotion you know and she could hold audiences in the palm of her hand

00:31:13.720 --> 00:31:21.180
[Guest]: as such and you see that the before they were leaders who were they you know this is a question

00:31:21.180 --> 00:31:26.240
[Guest]: I keep going back to with everything before we were authors before we identified ourselves

00:31:26.240 --> 00:31:34.040
[Guest]: as whatever what was it that we were moving towards and you see those early whispers of

00:31:34.040 --> 00:31:40.080
[Guest]: self-respect of challenging the history that you've been given and saying that no you know

00:31:40.080 --> 00:31:46.380
[Guest]: the British did not make us a whole and a collective and a people the land and the history

00:31:46.380 --> 00:31:52.280
[Guest]: of the land does not fully make us Indians because we did not think of ourselves as Indians

00:31:52.280 --> 00:31:59.040
[Guest]: before that but here we are at this moment in time and we can literally imagine ourselves

00:31:59.040 --> 00:32:04.920
[Guest]: into being I think it's remarkable that the Constitution which is a written document after

00:32:04.920 --> 00:32:10.840
[Guest]: all you know everywhere after a while when I saw the freedom struggle slightly differently

00:32:10.840 --> 00:32:15.680
[Guest]: I started to see it as a thing that was held together not just by protests as important

00:32:15.680 --> 00:32:23.960
[Guest]: as they were and by actions but by breath and speech and writing and imagining you really

00:32:23.960 --> 00:32:30.080
[Guest]: have to imagine a country into being you know that's the other side of being a nation okay

00:32:30.080 --> 00:32:35.200
[Guest]: I've gotten my soapbox long enough I need to shut up and give you a chance to. Lots

00:32:35.200 --> 00:32:39.320
[Amit Varma]: to think about like Joan Didion once said I don't know what I think until I write it

00:32:39.320 --> 00:32:44.040
[Amit Varma]: down and when you speak of you know all the letters these people wrote and a lot of it

00:32:44.040 --> 00:32:48.360
[Amit Varma]: is online like the hundred volumes of Gandhi's collected writings online and they're just

00:32:48.360 --> 00:32:53.040
[Amit Varma]: fascinating one little collection that I especially love is his correspondence with Tagore where

00:32:53.040 --> 00:32:57.400
[Amit Varma]: they're writing to each other all the time disagreeing but so full of love for each other

00:32:57.400 --> 00:33:02.920
[Guest]: you know so different from the discourse today and Amit have we lost that I don't don't mean

00:33:02.920 --> 00:33:09.000
[Guest]: you to lose the thread but just in parenthesis have we lost that the ability to disagree

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:14.320
[Guest]: over even a long period of time even passionately but to disagree without hating each other

00:33:14.320 --> 00:33:19.880
[Guest]: without putting each other down and coming back to what you said continuing that ability

00:33:19.880 --> 00:33:25.440
[Amit Varma]: to listen anyway I'm just putting that I'll come back to that but my short answer is yes

00:33:25.440 --> 00:33:30.160
[Amit Varma]: but I'll come back to that and we'll explore it and let me let me you know you can disagree

00:33:30.160 --> 00:33:35.280
[Amit Varma]: with me and we'll still be friends but yeah but my thread was that and this is again something

00:33:35.280 --> 00:33:40.160
[Amit Varma]: I spoke of I think with Amitabh Kumar in my episode with him and with again our mutual

00:33:40.160 --> 00:33:43.320
[Amit Varma]: friend Chandrahas Chaudhary though that's not released yet but the thought actually

00:33:43.320 --> 00:33:49.280
[Amit Varma]: came to me when Chandrahas once wrote me an email I sent him an email into inviting him

00:33:49.280 --> 00:33:54.520
[Amit Varma]: to the show and he sent me this long charming reply which was like a letter of yore you

00:33:54.520 --> 00:34:00.280
[Amit Varma]: know when you'd sit down and you'd write three-page letters two-page letters you know with memories

00:34:00.280 --> 00:34:04.560
[Amit Varma]: and you remember we were in Pune and we had samosa at that place and all of that so such

00:34:04.560 --> 00:34:08.680
[Amit Varma]: a rich letter and that got me to thinking about correspondence that when I was younger

00:34:08.680 --> 00:34:13.600
[Amit Varma]: before the internet I would also write letters you know I have also written letters to my

00:34:13.600 --> 00:34:18.120
[Amit Varma]: parents talking about you know talking at length about anything at all but talking at

00:34:18.120 --> 00:34:23.680
[Amit Varma]: length which is the whole point and this goes back to the question I asked earlier about

00:34:23.680 --> 00:34:28.800
[Amit Varma]: how form can shape the content can shape the person because when you are writing a letter

00:34:28.800 --> 00:34:34.920
[Amit Varma]: you are giving yourself in to a certain kind of reflection to a certain kind of thought

00:34:34.920 --> 00:34:41.000
[Amit Varma]: today we are an age where everything is a two-line email or it's an you know you're

00:34:41.000 --> 00:34:45.840
[Amit Varma]: sending an emoji by whatsapp and everything is crisp and everything is instrumental and

00:34:45.840 --> 00:34:51.120
[Amit Varma]: it's very rare that we are doing that kind of considered communication with each other

00:34:51.120 --> 00:34:56.400
[Amit Varma]: and the act of writing a letter to someone is not just an act of sitting and having to

00:34:56.400 --> 00:35:00.280
[Amit Varma]: flesh out your thoughts again going back to Diddy and I don't know what I think until

00:35:00.280 --> 00:35:04.200
[Amit Varma]: I write it down so the act of fleshing out your thoughts and therefore discovering what

00:35:04.200 --> 00:35:10.240
[Amit Varma]: you think in a sense and discovering yourself but it is also the act of giving respect to

00:35:10.240 --> 00:35:14.600
[Amit Varma]: another person you know giving that time that you're sitting down and you're writing a letter

00:35:14.600 --> 00:35:22.120
[Amit Varma]: to someone and that means that person is important and today you don't have that even as a signaling

00:35:22.120 --> 00:35:26.200
[Amit Varma]: device of someone's importance you don't have that but more than that you no longer have

00:35:26.200 --> 00:35:33.320
[Amit Varma]: that space to kind of sit down and reflect everything is so short instrumental crisp

00:35:33.320 --> 00:35:37.760
[Amit Varma]: and it's great that we can just reach out to each other you know anytime we want and

00:35:37.760 --> 00:35:45.440
[Amit Varma]: all of that but do you know just with not being nostalgic for a particular form of writing

00:35:45.440 --> 00:35:52.240
[Amit Varma]: but just in terms of the larger meta question of does it then change us as a society because

00:35:52.240 --> 00:35:57.920
[Amit Varma]: the form has changed because we no longer have those moments of quiet and reflection

00:35:57.920 --> 00:36:03.640
[Amit Varma]: and because we are no longer making those kinds of mental efforts and because the rhythms

00:36:03.640 --> 00:36:08.280
[Amit Varma]: of our life are much more much choppier and much quicker I see where you're going with

00:36:08.280 --> 00:36:14.960
[Guest]: this and it's not just the time to sit down and think and reflect because you can write

00:36:14.960 --> 00:36:20.920
[Guest]: letters at high speed as well but it's more like the kind of speed that's expected in

00:36:20.920 --> 00:36:27.920
[Guest]: Twitter exchanges you have to address something now and in that moment of a controversy exploding

00:36:27.920 --> 00:36:32.640
[Guest]: the urgency is sharp and immediate but by tomorrow everyone's forgotten so one of the

00:36:32.640 --> 00:36:38.720
[Guest]: biggest problems we have is that we live in a state of perpetual amnesia right and when

00:36:38.720 --> 00:36:47.600
[Guest]: you have that as an affliction for society you are no longer in touch with your own psyche

00:36:47.600 --> 00:36:55.200
[Guest]: your own self right with letters I'm going to answer this a little discursively but I

00:36:55.200 --> 00:37:00.840
[Guest]: still have letters that I wrote to my school friends years ago and sometimes those contain

00:37:00.840 --> 00:37:06.600
[Guest]: years and years of correspondence and then you can mark the moment when emails arrived

00:37:06.600 --> 00:37:12.960
[Guest]: because suddenly the letters stop our first emails this was when you had stuff like Hotmail

00:37:12.960 --> 00:37:20.400
[Guest]: and Lycos around yeah our first emails for the first few years are really long we're

00:37:20.400 --> 00:37:25.760
[Guest]: trying to go back to letters in a sense because that's what we are familiar with and I noticed

00:37:25.760 --> 00:37:32.960
[Guest]: this years later when I was printing out my Lycos mailbox before dispatching that account

00:37:32.960 --> 00:37:39.560
[Guest]: unconsciously we were all from India writing to inland letter form length you know if I

00:37:39.560 --> 00:37:44.560
[Guest]: don't know whether this generation would remember that but unconsciously your mind was trained

00:37:44.560 --> 00:37:50.720
[Guest]: to three landscapes you were trained to write the postcard you were trained to write inland

00:37:50.720 --> 00:37:55.440
[Guest]: letter forms and you were trained to write the free-flowing letter for which you would

00:37:55.440 --> 00:38:03.160
[Guest]: buy onion skin paper you know and you'd dwell on your envelopes and it was very important

00:38:03.160 --> 00:38:09.400
[Guest]: also to go to the post office and say sir sir if Gandhiji ki stamp mat dena doosra stamp

00:38:09.400 --> 00:38:14.600
[Guest]: dena Asia at Games ki stamp hai aapke paas you know you wanted the stamps to be as fancy

00:38:14.600 --> 00:38:20.480
[Guest]: as the letters were we used to covet the bird stamps and all of that so there were so many

00:38:20.480 --> 00:38:27.120
[Guest]: parts to the letter it wasn't just writing it it was wait for the ink to dry tear up

00:38:27.120 --> 00:38:31.120
[Guest]: this draft because you have said too much from your heart you know to a boyfriend or

00:38:31.120 --> 00:38:35.920
[Guest]: something of the sort and put it back in and then put it into the envelope put the stamp

00:38:35.920 --> 00:38:40.880
[Guest]: down then all the secret little hearts and flowers that the women used to write to each

00:38:40.880 --> 00:38:46.920
[Guest]: other you know so all of that Tehzeeb all of that ritual and everything goes away at

00:38:46.920 --> 00:38:53.840
[Guest]: some point we find ways to bring it back but I remember some years ago when my friend Margaret

00:38:53.840 --> 00:39:01.040
[Guest]: Mascarinehurst who was an incredible writer and poet in Goa when she died it was a sad

00:39:01.040 --> 00:39:08.520
[Guest]: thing to have only whatsapp messages to archive you know because we met in person the whatsapp

00:39:08.520 --> 00:39:14.800
[Guest]: messages became they served a different purpose then they became like little pointers whatsapp

00:39:14.800 --> 00:39:18.920
[Guest]: to each other about this on this day and then suddenly a memory of a conversation would

00:39:18.920 --> 00:39:25.000
[Guest]: open up but they really know more than memorial aids you know thumbnails they don't have the

00:39:25.000 --> 00:39:31.000
[Guest]: satisfaction that accompanies letter writing but right now if you ask this generation take

00:39:31.000 --> 00:39:36.960
[Guest]: some time out you might get people to do one letter who is going to sit down and do the

00:39:36.960 --> 00:39:44.200
[Guest]: full chain you know that business of you set aside some time every week to write letters

00:39:44.200 --> 00:39:51.080
[Guest]: you go on holiday and you write a letter that also indicates a certain faith in we've been

00:39:51.080 --> 00:39:56.800
[Guest]: talking about speed and the amnesia and the other part of it let us bespeak a kind of

00:39:56.800 --> 00:40:04.720
[Guest]: permanence and a faith in the record so somewhere unconsciously as our handwriting has gone

00:40:04.720 --> 00:40:09.760
[Guest]: I think we've also it's I wouldn't call it a cause but I would say it's gone hand in

00:40:09.760 --> 00:40:17.560
[Guest]: hand with this very modern lack of faith in the historical record you see what I mean

00:40:17.560 --> 00:40:23.120
[Guest]: when everything is impermanent and everything dissolves and everything can be killed once

00:40:23.120 --> 00:40:29.060
[Guest]: a particular social media platform shuts down you can use lose years and years of photographs

00:40:29.060 --> 00:40:34.280
[Guest]: and notes if Facebook goes tomorrow or you can lose 40,000 tweets written over 10 years

00:40:34.280 --> 00:40:41.240
[Guest]: if Twitter goes tomorrow and somehow increasingly these interactions I'm still on Twitter because

00:40:41.240 --> 00:40:48.920
[Guest]: that hook is there you know what is that hook it's partly the fear of missing out it's partly

00:40:48.920 --> 00:40:54.080
[Guest]: and this is the nice side of it the desire to keep in touch with people who are there

00:40:54.080 --> 00:40:58.480
[Guest]: but partly and this is the dangerous side of it we all think we immune and we are not

00:40:58.480 --> 00:41:03.920
[Guest]: it doesn't matter how smart you are but social media the way it is formulated in present

00:41:03.920 --> 00:41:11.000
[Guest]: days is built to be sticky we know that you know I can spend five minutes on Twitter fine

00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:16.200
[Guest]: if I spend half an hour on Twitter my days gone and after a while my moods my emotions

00:41:16.200 --> 00:41:23.440
[Guest]: those very intimate personal things have changed instead if you train yourself to back away

00:41:23.440 --> 00:41:29.640
[Guest]: and to use it then you lose what we had when we first found Twitter if you remember Twitter

00:41:29.640 --> 00:41:35.120
[Guest]: was all about finding a new way of expressing yourself and that's also what the first-generation

00:41:35.120 --> 00:41:43.160
[Guest]: web was about Hussein Deirakshan who's the Iranian blogger who went through an incredible

00:41:43.160 --> 00:41:48.440
[Guest]: and very saddening experience he was held in jail for many years and when he came out

00:41:48.440 --> 00:41:54.160
[Guest]: among the many dislocations he faced was a real sense that the world itself had changed

00:41:54.160 --> 00:41:59.680
[Guest]: because the net as he knew it the World Wide Web had changed beyond recognition and he

00:41:59.680 --> 00:42:04.680
[Guest]: was one of the first people to write about the fact that when you had blogs they created

00:42:04.680 --> 00:42:11.160
[Guest]: a universe of islands that were linked but you weren't you weren't content does that

00:42:11.160 --> 00:42:16.640
[Guest]: make sense that makes a lot of sense yeah and today I think when everything is being

00:42:16.640 --> 00:42:21.720
[Guest]: massaged into content and brands and all of that and I'm absolutely not averse to the

00:42:21.720 --> 00:42:26.120
[Guest]: pursuit of success through writing all the things all I want to say is that there are

00:42:26.120 --> 00:42:32.920
[Guest]: deeper satisfactions you know writing just isn't just about having a best-selling book

00:42:32.920 --> 00:42:40.600
[Guest]: out there or having the great career or whatever if you really want to write a lot of writers

00:42:40.600 --> 00:42:45.600
[Guest]: started off telling stories or being part of the weave of having stories told to them

00:42:45.600 --> 00:42:52.320
[Guest]: in my case it was my mother who became a lawyer at the age of 39 but before that you know

00:42:52.320 --> 00:42:56.640
[Guest]: she used to do these incredible bedtime stories where she'd look at whatever the pattern was

00:42:56.640 --> 00:43:01.200
[Guest]: on our curtains or whatever shadows there were on the wall and make up things about

00:43:01.200 --> 00:43:05.920
[Guest]: that and you don't even realize you don't use the formal words my imagination is being

00:43:05.920 --> 00:43:13.760
[Guest]: trained but what you learn is double at this point you learn that you are absolutely free

00:43:13.760 --> 00:43:19.080
[Guest]: to use your imagination in whichever way you want to and you also learn that even adults

00:43:19.080 --> 00:43:23.880
[Guest]: you know even parents even these people who have so much power over you have wonderful

00:43:23.880 --> 00:43:29.580
[Guest]: secret lives so right from the start what you start to learn is the importance of having

00:43:29.580 --> 00:43:35.880
[Guest]: this private self this individual self and if I may say so this whinely creative self

00:43:35.880 --> 00:43:41.200
[Guest]: I live in fear that creativity will become another one of those buzzwords you know but

00:43:41.200 --> 00:43:45.560
[Guest]: the truth is I think something we've been talking about for years and years among ourselves

00:43:45.560 --> 00:43:52.640
[Guest]: or whatever is with privilege without privilege how do you live lives that are more fully

00:43:52.640 --> 00:43:57.960
[Guest]: creative and I don't mean just formally creative I don't mean that you have to be a writer

00:43:57.960 --> 00:44:02.240
[Guest]: in the sense that you have to publish books so you have to be an artist in the sense of

00:44:02.240 --> 00:44:06.800
[Guest]: you have to have a painting exhibition I'm not talking about the outcome or the productivity

00:44:06.800 --> 00:44:13.640
[Guest]: but I'm saying a life of consumption which is what we increasingly have been driven towards

00:44:13.640 --> 00:44:19.200
[Guest]: consumption not just in terms of buying things that you then show off but in terms of your

00:44:19.200 --> 00:44:29.000
[Guest]: most intimate moments are held out for display or that your identity is as a clever consumer

00:44:29.000 --> 00:44:36.160
[Guest]: of life right if you shift that paradigm just a little bit and I mean by the way you really

00:44:36.160 --> 00:44:40.160
[Amit Varma]: have to stop me when I start going down segways or whatever I love these segways and I will

00:44:40.160 --> 00:44:47.360
[Guest]: never stop you I think right from the start I've been asking myself even from early childhood

00:44:47.360 --> 00:44:54.440
[Guest]: what does it mean to be truly creative because to me that is the life that humans derive

00:44:54.440 --> 00:44:59.480
[Guest]: the most not even pleasure not even benefit from but that's where we are at our best we

00:44:59.480 --> 00:45:06.000
[Amit Varma]: are creative animals no and and what you were saying earlier about you know letters in history

00:45:06.000 --> 00:45:10.480
[Amit Varma]: the connection reminds me of this Agha Shahid Ali quote which you've quoted in your book

00:45:10.480 --> 00:45:16.000
[Amit Varma]: as well my memory gets in the way of your history and that sort of feels so apt and

00:45:16.000 --> 00:45:21.720
[Amit Varma]: again what you you know the point you made about Twitter is you know that for five minutes

00:45:21.720 --> 00:45:25.280
[Amit Varma]: is okay for half an hour it destroys your day and that's literally what it does because

00:45:25.280 --> 00:45:29.240
[Amit Varma]: it changes the rhythm of your brain because the rhythm of your brain is doing hop skip

00:45:29.240 --> 00:45:33.960
[Amit Varma]: step jump duck duck duck duck is going like that instead of being in a quieter place so

00:45:33.960 --> 00:45:38.920
[Amit Varma]: you might want to you know do two hours of focused work on whatever it is but if you

00:45:38.920 --> 00:45:43.040
[Amit Varma]: put your brain in that quick rhythm where you're skipping from one thing to the other

00:45:43.040 --> 00:45:48.280
[Amit Varma]: then it becomes difficult you know it's probably better to begin the day by meditation or something

00:45:48.280 --> 00:45:53.400
[Amit Varma]: but except that I don't do meditation I do Twitter which is a problem my next question

00:45:53.400 --> 00:45:57.600
[Amit Varma]: is about a subject that you know I spoke about with my guest last week and I've been thinking

00:45:57.600 --> 00:46:02.960
[Amit Varma]: about it a lot and it relates to a few things that you've said today I read this wonderful

00:46:02.960 --> 00:46:10.160
[Amit Varma]: book called wanting by Luke Burgess and you know Burgess is sort of a disciple and intellectual

00:46:10.160 --> 00:46:17.600
[Amit Varma]: disciple of Ren Girard the philosopher and Girard was once a few decades ago asked he's

00:46:17.600 --> 00:46:21.280
[Amit Varma]: a philosopher but he was asked to teach a course on literature and he needed the money

00:46:21.280 --> 00:46:26.800
[Amit Varma]: so he said okay I'll do it and he read through whatever he thought was a reading list and

00:46:26.800 --> 00:46:32.520
[Amit Varma]: the books he wanted to talk about and he discovered that the one thing he they all had in common

00:46:32.520 --> 00:46:37.080
[Amit Varma]: and he was probably being simplistic here I'm not sure I agree but it's still a profound

00:46:37.080 --> 00:46:42.260
[Amit Varma]: point he felt that the one thing all the characters had in common was that they wanted something

00:46:42.260 --> 00:46:48.240
[Amit Varma]: not because they intrinsically wanted that thing but because somebody else wanted it

00:46:48.240 --> 00:46:53.280
[Amit Varma]: and he coined the term mimetic desire mimetic of course you know coming from imitation the

00:46:53.280 --> 00:46:59.520
[Amit Varma]: idea being that you want something not because it's intrinsic to you but somebody else wants

00:46:59.520 --> 00:47:04.520
[Amit Varma]: it and you know it could be a yuppie wanting to buy the latest Mercedes or it could be

00:47:04.520 --> 00:47:08.120
[Amit Varma]: a young person wanting to get married and settle down because hey that's what everyone

00:47:08.120 --> 00:47:12.680
[Amit Varma]: does and that's what is expected so you're like I want that too but you don't ever examine

00:47:12.680 --> 00:47:18.680
[Amit Varma]: it or think about it deeply and the framework that I got from Burgess's book which I find

00:47:18.680 --> 00:47:25.520
[Amit Varma]: really useful is of thick and thin desires where thick desires are intrinsic to you you

00:47:25.520 --> 00:47:29.520
[Amit Varma]: know they are deep they are what you really desire they come from within you right and

00:47:29.520 --> 00:47:34.040
[Amit Varma]: when we talk of thick and thin obviously it's understood that all the creature necessities

00:47:34.040 --> 00:47:38.080
[Amit Varma]: like you know food shelter all that is not in this everybody wants that that's okay that's

00:47:38.080 --> 00:47:42.960
[Amit Varma]: understood but otherwise you have thick desires for the things that you really really want

00:47:42.960 --> 00:47:49.080
[Amit Varma]: and you have thin desires which are things that you want because of different factors

00:47:49.080 --> 00:47:54.160
[Amit Varma]: in the environment maybe somebody else wants it maybe it'll get you the approval of others

00:47:54.160 --> 00:48:02.200
[Amit Varma]: so on and so forth and the problem is that thin desires can often be intense so the thing

00:48:02.200 --> 00:48:07.280
[Amit Varma]: that you want the most right now you know is probably not the thing that you really

00:48:07.280 --> 00:48:11.720
[Amit Varma]: want the most that comes from inside you may want it very badly for example the quest for

00:48:11.720 --> 00:48:16.440
[Amit Varma]: validation which can lead so many people to do the things they do on Twitter we'll talk

00:48:16.440 --> 00:48:21.680
[Amit Varma]: about that also and so on or when you speak about writers you know you spoke about how

00:48:21.680 --> 00:48:27.520
[Amit Varma]: some writers are you know more in love with the idea of being writers I want to get something

00:48:27.520 --> 00:48:32.800
[Amit Varma]: published I want to be nominated for an award rather than loving the act of writing itself

00:48:32.800 --> 00:48:37.880
[Amit Varma]: which is on the printed page and I imagine loving the act of writing itself you know

00:48:37.880 --> 00:48:42.080
[Amit Varma]: would be a thick desire because it can only really come from within where you enjoy what

00:48:42.080 --> 00:48:47.480
[Amit Varma]: you're creating and the stories that you're telling whereas wanting to be a writer could

00:48:47.480 --> 00:48:54.880
[Amit Varma]: be a sort of a thin desire and this is caused me to sort of reflect on why do I want the

00:48:54.880 --> 00:49:00.560
[Amit Varma]: things that I want you know what are my thick and thin desires in a sense and I'd encourage

00:49:00.560 --> 00:49:08.120
[Amit Varma]: all listeners to also kind of think about this in their own context but in your context

00:49:08.120 --> 00:49:15.440
[Amit Varma]: then looking back what would you say would be your thick desires and what would you say

00:49:15.440 --> 00:49:20.200
[Amit Varma]: would be the things that you wanted but now you feel bad that you wanted them that you

00:49:20.200 --> 00:49:27.040
[Amit Varma]: should not have wanted those kind of directions you went down on I think I love the way you

00:49:27.040 --> 00:49:34.760
[Guest]: come at questions because you're asking us by and large during the podcast to tap into

00:49:34.760 --> 00:49:39.800
[Guest]: something that is deeper than just the automatic list of the 10 books that influenced you or

00:49:39.800 --> 00:49:46.880
[Guest]: what made you want to be a writer or whatever and I think my deepest desires were for a

00:49:46.880 --> 00:49:54.200
[Guest]: combination of privacy and experience and immersion particularly into the world of stories

00:49:54.200 --> 00:49:57.960
[Guest]: one of the thick desires that I didn't act on for many years because I was terrified

00:49:57.960 --> 00:50:04.520
[Guest]: of actually making it happen was that was writing I came to writing very late I don't

00:50:04.520 --> 00:50:08.680
[Guest]: mean that I came to writing late actually I've been writing for a living from the time

00:50:08.680 --> 00:50:14.200
[Guest]: I was about 19 or 20 I think I wrote my first book review when I was 15 years old or something

00:50:14.200 --> 00:50:21.040
[Guest]: of the sort obnoxious in that sense we Bengalis what can I say but I was working at the business

00:50:21.040 --> 00:50:30.600
[Guest]: standard by the time I was 19 years old 1920 yeah and I was with them for about 15 years

00:50:30.600 --> 00:50:36.840
[Guest]: or so I didn't really know how to want a career a lot of people asked me for advice on their

00:50:36.840 --> 00:50:44.480
[Guest]: writing career and I am blank about that I knew that I was curious about many many things

00:50:44.480 --> 00:50:51.480
[Guest]: I think my one of my deepest desires was just to both experience the world in every form

00:50:51.480 --> 00:50:56.680
[Guest]: so I was a travel writer I was a food writer for a while I was on the gender beat with

00:50:56.680 --> 00:51:04.080
[Guest]: the New York Times and I see that as just an urge to in this human lifetime in this

00:51:04.080 --> 00:51:10.640
[Guest]: human form reach out for as much of the world as possible that was far more important to

00:51:10.640 --> 00:51:16.280
[Guest]: me than material wealth status and all of that which in just as well I chose writing

00:51:16.280 --> 00:51:21.680
[Guest]: as a profession in that sense I will say in parenthesis that while writing hasn't made

00:51:21.680 --> 00:51:27.080
[Guest]: me you know ridiculously wealthy it's surprising that it doesn't make you that poor either

00:51:27.080 --> 00:51:31.600
[Guest]: it's it's possible to make a living doing something that you love which is one of the

00:51:31.600 --> 00:51:42.160
[Guest]: first things that we believe is not true you know a thick desire again just solitary exploration

00:51:42.160 --> 00:51:48.200
[Guest]: as a young girl in Delhi I think I'm militated against the fact that at a certain hour of

00:51:48.200 --> 00:51:55.560
[Guest]: the evening the city becomes a men's city and you can't walk safely as a woman and I

00:51:55.560 --> 00:52:01.720
[Guest]: was very diffident but also insistent that I should walk everywhere that I should you

00:52:01.720 --> 00:52:07.040
[Guest]: only see a city or know a city really whether it's London or Delhi or Calcutta or Bombay

00:52:07.040 --> 00:52:11.320
[Guest]: it's only on foot that you really get the pulse of it the beat of it the sense of it

00:52:11.320 --> 00:52:17.840
[Guest]: outside of your own neighborhoods right and there you have it you know a question I think

00:52:17.840 --> 00:52:26.480
[Guest]: for me being in movement creating not for a prize and not for a book contract but just

00:52:26.480 --> 00:52:32.600
[Guest]: the work ultimately it keeps coming back in the writing to me and the page I like people

00:52:32.600 --> 00:52:37.480
[Guest]: to be able to read through whatever I'm writing very swiftly but I also like the work that

00:52:37.480 --> 00:52:43.200
[Guest]: goes into making that read a swift read I like them to walk away whether I'm writing

00:52:43.200 --> 00:52:48.480
[Guest]: about cats or humans with the feeling that they have been in a real world and a world

00:52:48.480 --> 00:52:54.040
[Guest]: that is maybe a little more intense and more real than the world that surrounds you again

00:52:54.040 --> 00:52:58.520
[Guest]: I have a habit of segwaying and traveling very far from the question that you asked

00:52:58.520 --> 00:53:05.320
[Guest]: but I was very fortunate when I was in my 20s in my first job again at the Business

00:53:05.320 --> 00:53:11.760
[Guest]: Standard and then later as a young editor at Penguin to meet a lot of writers and artists

00:53:11.760 --> 00:53:18.160
[Guest]: in Delhi at a time before success had in that sense touched and transformed both the art

00:53:18.160 --> 00:53:25.840
[Guest]: world and the literary world so MF Hussain at that point of time had his own right painting

00:53:25.840 --> 00:53:34.040
[Guest]: studio he was already becoming the big financial success that he was but for most other painters

00:53:34.040 --> 00:53:38.840
[Guest]: there wasn't that much money on the table per se that didn't lead to a life of great

00:53:38.840 --> 00:53:44.200
[Guest]: purity it just meant that there was a freedom in the way that they were writing there were

00:53:44.200 --> 00:53:49.040
[Guest]: a handful of galleries that were exhibiting their work and so it was for writers you know

00:53:49.040 --> 00:53:54.960
[Guest]: for Amitav Ghosh sitting in a Barsati in defense colony writing his first books and shaving

00:53:54.960 --> 00:54:01.680
[Guest]: off half his hair as incentive to keep him indoors writing and not outdoors distracted

00:54:01.680 --> 00:54:08.480
[Guest]: or for Shahid Agha Shahid Ali you know coming out with his poems in which he puts pain and

00:54:08.480 --> 00:54:15.240
[Guest]: love and a sense of foreboding because I think Shahid was one of those people who saw many

00:54:15.240 --> 00:54:21.600
[Guest]: many years ago the future to which Kashmir was inexorably moving I don't think he had

00:54:21.600 --> 00:54:27.400
[Guest]: any defenses against the truth but with all of these writers I spent a lot of my time

00:54:27.400 --> 00:54:32.600
[Guest]: in writer student studios you know in Gari village with meeting ceramic artists like

00:54:32.600 --> 00:54:39.120
[Guest]: Joy Michael and Gina Franklin Gupta and a huge suite of people and every now and then

00:54:39.120 --> 00:54:44.320
[Guest]: business standard would push me out and make me interview fashion designers which is how

00:54:44.320 --> 00:54:51.000
[Guest]: I came to accidentally dance in Milan Soman's direction while I was still wearing a khadi

00:54:51.000 --> 00:54:57.800
[Guest]: kurta from Khadi Gramodiyag Bhavan. Is this on tape? Have you danced? Thank God! No! What

00:54:57.800 --> 00:55:04.920
[Guest]: was this? It was a fashion show it was an early fashion show where Rohit Bal was just

00:55:04.920 --> 00:55:09.920
[Guest]: and Tarun Tehriani were just about breaking through and there was so much snobbery and

00:55:09.920 --> 00:55:15.320
[Guest]: deadly you know the initial reaction to this generation of fashion geniuses from Rohit

00:55:15.320 --> 00:55:23.120
[Guest]: Bal and Tarun Tehriani to Reena Dhaka and the rest was Hai unke beta toh darzi ban gaya

00:55:23.120 --> 00:55:29.560
[Guest]: you know that boy has gone and become a tailor and then of course liberalization happened

00:55:29.560 --> 00:55:35.120
[Guest]: India hit the stratosphere but this was just a little before that he took the first few

00:55:35.120 --> 00:55:41.080
[Guest]: fashion shows with the proper catwalk and a ramp and stuff and I was sent off to cover

00:55:41.080 --> 00:55:47.080
[Guest]: this and I bought a dress specifically for this I remember this because at that time

00:55:47.080 --> 00:55:52.720
[Guest]: Delhi didn't have much in the way of places where you could buy fancy clothes and I went

00:55:52.720 --> 00:55:56.520
[Guest]: off and bought a dress which in retrospect was a horror I remember very little about

00:55:56.520 --> 00:56:02.520
[Guest]: it except that I'm sure there were frills involved and puff sleeves or padded sleeves

00:56:02.520 --> 00:56:10.440
[Guest]: padded sleeves yeah the 80s power woman padded sleeve which had lasted into the early 90s

00:56:10.440 --> 00:56:16.560
[Guest]: let's draw a merciful vein over this memory but I wasn't able to get back home from the

00:56:16.560 --> 00:56:20.960
[Guest]: office in time so I went off to this fashion show in what I was wearing which happened

00:56:20.960 --> 00:56:27.280
[Guest]: to be a khadi kurta which is not what you wear to a fashion show then or now but you

00:56:27.280 --> 00:56:33.080
[Guest]: know bless them they were very warm and inviting and suddenly the music starts up and I'm on

00:56:33.080 --> 00:56:38.040
[Guest]: the catwalk I mean I was at the side of the catwalk but the catwalk was basically a red

00:56:38.040 --> 00:56:43.720
[Guest]: carpet on the ground and the music was contagious that was a less formal time and all of us

00:56:43.720 --> 00:56:49.640
[Guest]: started dancing and I turn around and there's this sweet guy with a lot of muscles who's

00:56:49.640 --> 00:56:55.480
[Guest]: quite good-looking and he dances a little bit in my direction I'm like okay you know

00:56:55.480 --> 00:57:00.600
[Guest]: he's a good dancer yeah he has the beat whatever and then I asked somebody who's he and they

00:57:00.600 --> 00:57:08.040
[Guest]: say Minin Soman yeah he's a supermodel already at that time one little brush with fame Delhi

00:57:08.040 --> 00:57:14.000
[Guest]: in that time was a lot of fun though but it was fun also because it was informal it was

00:57:14.000 --> 00:57:19.800
[Guest]: the kind of place where the writer Alan Sene used to play guitar at this little place called

00:57:19.800 --> 00:57:26.440
[Guest]: The Cellar which was one of the two or three places that you could go to for entertainment

00:57:26.440 --> 00:57:32.760
[Guest]: the first discos had started up Gungroo and my kind of place and I guess we led this kind

00:57:32.760 --> 00:57:37.680
[Guest]: of double life you know we were not most of us didn't have much pocket money you didn't

00:57:37.680 --> 00:57:45.040
[Guest]: have the chance to really work at jobs and stuff but if you could afford the entrance

00:57:45.040 --> 00:57:50.480
[Guest]: fee for Gungroo then you could dance the night away discos didn't shut down till about six

00:57:50.480 --> 00:57:56.700
[Guest]: in the morning if ever you know so you'd finish that and go to the clarages and everybody

00:57:56.700 --> 00:58:01.920
[Guest]: there'd be about eight people sitting there ordering one pot of coffee and bless their

00:58:01.920 --> 00:58:06.480
[Guest]: hearts they let us do that they were kind about that but getting back to the writers

00:58:06.480 --> 00:58:12.320
[Guest]: and the artists in their studio I think the three things I learned from them is the work

00:58:12.320 --> 00:58:17.160
[Guest]: itself is often messy and the opposite of joyful and you will be cursing as you do your

00:58:17.160 --> 00:58:23.720
[Guest]: first drafts or your early sketches or whatever but there is a joy to the work itself does

00:58:23.720 --> 00:58:31.800
[Guest]: that make sense everybody and some of the writers were drunks by their second profession

00:58:31.800 --> 00:58:37.640
[Guest]: you know a lot of the artists were happening into a range of other vices and pursuits and

00:58:37.640 --> 00:58:42.680
[Guest]: parties and this that and the other but the one thing that they all did was they showed

00:58:42.680 --> 00:58:49.080
[Guest]: up if you were serious about being a writer or an artist you owed it to yourself and to

00:58:49.080 --> 00:58:55.800
[Guest]: the work more than anything else not to the craft you know not to your vocation or reputation

00:58:55.800 --> 00:59:01.160
[Guest]: or yes sir but to the work itself to just show up day after day and the third thing

00:59:01.160 --> 00:59:05.760
[Guest]: was take some joy in what you're making you know don't try to write like somebody else

00:59:05.760 --> 00:59:12.020
[Guest]: Vikram Seth didn't get to write a suitable boy by trying to imitate a Steinbeck or somebody

00:59:12.020 --> 00:59:19.600
[Guest]: else if you see what I mean Arundhati Roy didn't find her voice by trying to be somebody

00:59:19.600 --> 00:59:24.560
[Guest]: other than she was I think that was the biggest thing that I started to pick up as well tell

00:59:24.560 --> 00:59:31.680
[Guest]: your own stories that generation was not focused on success very much the next generation has

00:59:31.680 --> 00:59:37.360
[Guest]: learned how to negotiate the world of celebrity television and what to do on a lit fest stage

00:59:37.360 --> 00:59:44.160
[Guest]: and all of that and I think when all of that is fun it's sometimes the part of lit fest

00:59:44.160 --> 00:59:49.120
[Guest]: that is great is really getting to meet readers for me and the other part of it it's wise

00:59:49.120 --> 00:59:55.760
[Guest]: to think of it as dress up you know you get to play dress up and go out but maybe not

00:59:55.760 --> 01:00:01.160
[Guest]: take it too seriously I think over the course of a lifetime I've also seen how a lot of

01:00:01.160 --> 01:00:07.040
[Guest]: writers can stop writing after having done some great work this one whom I don't want

01:00:07.040 --> 01:00:13.520
[Guest]: to name but you know whose books have got weaker and weaker as their public life has

01:00:13.520 --> 01:00:18.480
[Guest]: become more and more important and you sense at some point that the writer lives in the

01:00:18.480 --> 01:00:24.320
[Guest]: shadow of the books and that the public appearances this whole thing about speaking in public

01:00:24.320 --> 01:00:30.520
[Guest]: and being important and even the good stuff of supporting this cause or that cause the

01:00:30.520 --> 01:00:37.440
[Guest]: truth of it is that most of writing doesn't even happen on the page it happens in a pact

01:00:37.440 --> 01:00:41.760
[Guest]: of silence and unless you give the I think this is something we've been moving towards

01:00:41.760 --> 01:00:48.600
[Guest]: from the start of the conversation it's a question of where do you find rich ground

01:00:48.600 --> 01:00:55.400
[Guest]: and it is true that many of us come to these places from a lot of privilege but I will

01:00:55.400 --> 01:01:02.080
[Guest]: also say that wealth and comfort are not the pathways to writing I mean just a simple observation

01:01:02.080 --> 01:01:07.920
[Guest]: that many people have made before me if that was true then the rich would be writers right

01:01:07.920 --> 01:01:13.840
[Guest]: and the rich aren't really and the reason that they aren't is because actually writing

01:01:13.840 --> 01:01:19.080
[Guest]: actually creating something and then having the patience to go back and revise we all

01:01:19.080 --> 01:01:23.760
[Guest]: fall in love with the first things that tumble out of our mouths and all of that the fact

01:01:23.760 --> 01:01:30.080
[Guest]: is that most bits of writing are not much good unless there's some revision or some

01:01:30.080 --> 01:01:36.960
[Guest]: craft to it and I find that either the craft comes in before a lot of people do the outlining

01:01:36.960 --> 01:01:41.640
[Guest]: and the plotting and all of that even if they're just holding it in their magnificent heads

01:01:41.640 --> 01:01:48.720
[Guest]: or it comes in after but it's very rare for writing not to have craft even at the popular

01:01:48.720 --> 01:01:54.560
[Guest]: end of the scale and popular is not to be sneered at but someone like Stephen King someone

01:01:54.560 --> 01:02:00.640
[Guest]: like Daniel Steele someone like Chetan Bhagat they work really hard at the craft of getting

01:02:00.640 --> 01:02:08.360
[Guest]: people to continue to read and identify and feel something you see what I mean all these

01:02:08.360 --> 01:02:13.640
[Guest]: years anyway I should again hand it back to you because I'm about to deliver a lecture

01:02:13.640 --> 01:02:14.640
[Amit Varma]: on a craft.

01:02:14.640 --> 01:02:18.080
[Amit Varma]: It's also fascinating there are so many strands I want to kind of pull at till they unravel

01:02:18.080 --> 01:02:24.320
[Amit Varma]: completely and the padded shoulder dissolves can you elaborate a bit on what you said about

01:02:24.320 --> 01:02:27.720
[Amit Varma]: most of writing not happening on the page?

01:02:27.720 --> 01:02:32.680
[Guest]: I think so much happens particularly with a novel but this is true also of short stories

01:02:32.680 --> 01:02:39.800
[Guest]: and possibly every form of writing except for the poem poems can happen to you as you

01:02:39.800 --> 01:02:45.840
[Guest]: know a lot of poets report the experience of feeling the poem more or less take you

01:02:45.840 --> 01:02:50.720
[Guest]: by your collar and just run through you and all you have to do is to write it down and

01:02:50.720 --> 01:02:53.880
[Guest]: then continue to revise or whatever.

01:02:53.880 --> 01:03:00.280
[Guest]: In every other form of writing inspiration is important essential all of that but if

01:03:00.280 --> 01:03:04.240
[Guest]: you've been working in the field of writing whether you're doing screenplays or whatever

01:03:04.240 --> 01:03:08.600
[Guest]: you know actually that idea generation is the least of it.

01:03:08.600 --> 01:03:15.000
[Guest]: In between books I struggle for a while because I have no lack of ideas it's the opposite

01:03:15.000 --> 01:03:20.640
[Guest]: I have an idea a minute you know there's exercise books filled with ideas for short stories

01:03:20.640 --> 01:03:28.960
[Guest]: ranging from the risible to the hmm this might work but you only have so much time right

01:03:28.960 --> 01:03:35.960
[Guest]: and the imagination is the thing that we tend to skip over when we are talking about writing

01:03:35.960 --> 01:03:41.560
[Guest]: a lot of discussions particularly American influence discussions go immediately to craft

01:03:41.560 --> 01:03:48.160
[Guest]: to style to plot to voice all of that those are not unimportant but I think you know what

01:03:48.160 --> 01:03:56.120
[Guest]: you're doing with your course as well is training people to the idea of the practice itself

01:03:56.120 --> 01:04:01.280
[Guest]: and what is that practice it's just a way of turning on the headlights of the imagination

01:04:01.280 --> 01:04:09.920
[Guest]: and turning on the terrain and that old classic question where do ideas come from Neil Gaiman

01:04:09.920 --> 01:04:14.160
[Guest]: used to say there's a little shop down the road and you know a man across the counter

01:04:14.160 --> 01:04:19.360
[Guest]: hands me my ideas every morning in a nice paper bag or something to that extent the

01:04:19.360 --> 01:04:26.840
[Guest]: truth is we don't know we don't know Elizabeth Gilbert again the author of Eat Pray Love

01:04:26.840 --> 01:04:33.760
[Guest]: she's talked about the surreal but very real and very commonplace experience of having

01:04:33.760 --> 01:04:40.440
[Guest]: an idea for a book that you haven't worked on and you let it go and four years later

01:04:40.440 --> 01:04:47.040
[Guest]: somebody else comes up with that book in total and the first time it happens it's eerie it's

01:04:47.040 --> 01:04:52.840
[Guest]: not plagiarism but it feels like a theft from your unconscious until you realize that you're

01:04:52.840 --> 01:04:57.320
[Guest]: in spooky territory out here you are part of the collective unconscious of course there's

01:04:57.320 --> 01:05:03.200
[Guest]: a possibility that maybe the idea wasn't that precious after all some years back when I

01:05:03.200 --> 01:05:08.880
[Guest]: was just about starting out on the notes that became Black River and I knew I wanted to

01:05:08.880 --> 01:05:15.000
[Guest]: do a thriller I knew I wanted it set in Delhi I knew that it wasn't going to be about people

01:05:15.000 --> 01:05:20.760
[Guest]: like me and so it would require some research I knew that the river played a large part

01:05:20.760 --> 01:05:27.600
[Guest]: in it and I knew that it was about heartbreak and grief and I knew nothing else and this

01:05:27.600 --> 01:05:32.120
[Guest]: idea skated around my head why don't you write about Sheherazade instead you know bring her

01:05:32.120 --> 01:05:38.240
[Guest]: into our contemporary times and what would she be now with the weight of everything that

01:05:38.240 --> 01:05:44.760
[Guest]: she's experienced and gone through she becomes this man's bride after seeing so many women

01:05:44.760 --> 01:05:50.360
[Guest]: killed you know literally a bed of blood and then she ends up married to this murderer

01:05:50.360 --> 01:05:53.520
[Guest]: you know for the rest of her life she wins her life back but the price of that seems

01:05:53.520 --> 01:05:59.160
[Guest]: pretty high maybe she's a drug addict and I never wrote that story because the truth

01:05:59.160 --> 01:06:04.760
[Guest]: of it is that Sheherazade's I do believe that we should be free to write with no limits

01:06:04.760 --> 01:06:11.680
[Guest]: on the imagination but I bump up against the difficulty of translating Sheherazade into

01:06:11.680 --> 01:06:17.360
[Guest]: my times there's just too much about her background her Middle Eastern life that I would not know

01:06:17.360 --> 01:06:24.120
[Guest]: or be comfortable with I tabled it many years later I read a book by another writer and

01:06:24.120 --> 01:06:31.200
[Guest]: beautifully done book where there's Sheherazade in modern times and she's an addict of sorts

01:06:31.200 --> 01:06:36.920
[Guest]: and I don't think anyone's stealing from anyone else it's just that that realm is mysterious

01:06:36.920 --> 01:06:43.960
[Guest]: but it's accessible to all if you train yourself and if you train the muscles of the imagination

01:06:43.960 --> 01:06:50.480
[Guest]: which are as real if you like as the muscles of a runner yeah so that's part of what happens

01:06:50.480 --> 01:06:57.320
[Guest]: off the page is learning to quieten down because nothing happens in the noise even the writers

01:06:57.320 --> 01:07:04.600
[Guest]: who go out you know in the middle of the hurdy-burdy of life the bars of Paris the slums of Bombay

01:07:04.600 --> 01:07:09.000
[Guest]: the permit rooms and all of that at some point you're gonna have to come back to quietness

01:07:09.000 --> 01:07:13.720
[Guest]: that's where it all starts that's the fertile ground at least you're gonna have to quiet

01:07:13.720 --> 01:07:18.840
[Guest]: down enough to hear the voices of the people that you're writing about right and then comes

01:07:18.840 --> 01:07:25.360
[Guest]: the shaping you know that can happen off the page in a very technical sense as in you might

01:07:25.360 --> 01:07:30.200
[Guest]: be doing your notes and outlines and all the crafty things that you do but I think some

01:07:30.200 --> 01:07:35.440
[Guest]: of that really happens when you're living in the classic two worlds you're not you're

01:07:35.440 --> 01:07:39.200
[Guest]: walking around you're talking to your partner and your friends you're going shopping and

01:07:39.200 --> 01:07:45.480
[Guest]: all of that but part of you really at that point of time truly is living somewhere else

01:07:45.480 --> 01:07:49.720
[Guest]: you know that's one reason why I find short stories which I don't know how to write but

01:07:49.720 --> 01:07:55.000
[Guest]: which I'm trying to learn how to write a little easier because you can't quite pop in and

01:07:55.000 --> 01:08:02.040
[Guest]: out it's just as intense but you don't have to spend years in that world right when I

01:08:02.040 --> 01:08:07.600
[Guest]: say most of the writing happens off the page there's another thing as well which is simply

01:08:07.600 --> 01:08:13.640
[Guest]: that everything you were before you turn to writing is also what you're bringing to the

01:08:13.640 --> 01:08:23.160
[Guest]: table right a lot of people want to be writers really young and I find myself not wanting

01:08:23.160 --> 01:08:29.840
[Guest]: to be discouraging but just wanting to say would you like to go and live a little you

01:08:29.840 --> 01:08:36.960
[Guest]: know don't the MFA by itself is a fine thing but try not to build a life maybe that's MFA

01:08:36.960 --> 01:08:45.560
[Guest]: and writing residencies and those slightly enclosed worlds if that makes sense that makes

01:08:45.560 --> 01:08:50.640
[Amit Varma]: a lot of sense and that's and that's something I found about myself when I was young also

01:08:50.640 --> 01:08:56.280
[Amit Varma]: that I wanted to write but I didn't have enough lived experience to be able to write meaningfully

01:08:56.280 --> 01:09:00.840
[Amit Varma]: about anything and then you went off and became a poker Marvin and all of that and then I

01:09:00.840 --> 01:09:05.400
[Amit Varma]: came back and now I have the lived experience but I don't have the discipline perhaps you

01:09:05.400 --> 01:09:10.280
[Amit Varma]: know it's ironic one of the one of the four webinars for my writing courses about process

01:09:10.280 --> 01:09:14.760
[Amit Varma]: and discipline and all of that and I feel so embarrassed because I'm just all of them

01:09:14.760 --> 01:09:19.400
[Amit Varma]: must be all my participants must be staggering as I listen to this but that I myself haven't

01:09:19.400 --> 01:09:25.640
[Amit Varma]: been able to put so much of that into practice though I place a certain stress on it because

01:09:25.640 --> 01:09:31.560
[Amit Varma]: partly because I know that that is the important thing that you actually have to you know sit

01:09:31.560 --> 01:09:36.400
[Amit Varma]: down and get the writing done and build those processes because ideas like you said are

01:09:36.400 --> 01:09:41.600
[Amit Varma]: just a dime a dozen but you know learning how to tell the stories and telling them and

01:09:41.600 --> 01:09:47.240
[Amit Varma]: that kind of also matters you know another thread from what you mentioned earlier and

01:09:47.240 --> 01:09:52.320
[Amit Varma]: that I want to kind of tug at I don't this is not a good metaphor not tugging at threads

01:09:52.320 --> 01:09:58.120
[Amit Varma]: is something that you've sort of written in your book again about when you were young

01:09:58.120 --> 01:10:04.600
[Amit Varma]: about the thrill of discovery where when you're describing yourself as a kid you are always

01:10:04.600 --> 01:10:08.400
[Amit Varma]: going up to strangers apparently jumping on their knees and demanding that they tell you

01:10:08.400 --> 01:10:15.080
[Amit Varma]: a story and this gets very irritating after the point but then you write quote I must

01:10:15.080 --> 01:10:19.800
[Amit Varma]: have been three when I realized that books contain stories the way tins contain biscuits

01:10:19.800 --> 01:10:24.160
[Amit Varma]: and from the time that I made that connection my mind was not at peace so much of childhood

01:10:24.160 --> 01:10:28.800
[Amit Varma]: is a balancing act between the first indelible rush of astonishment and discovery and the

01:10:28.800 --> 01:10:33.560
[Amit Varma]: inevitable grappling with frustration when he was three my young nephew named the shiny

01:10:33.560 --> 01:10:39.320
[Amit Varma]: thing in the sky a star using the word importantly and I could see the satisfaction in his eyes

01:10:39.320 --> 01:10:43.380
[Amit Varma]: the glory of naming everything in the world for the very first time ever as though no

01:10:43.380 --> 01:10:48.040
[Amit Varma]: human being had done this before him and no one would do this again those first thrills

01:10:48.040 --> 01:10:54.600
[Amit Varma]: of discovery are fierce and unforgettable stop quote and and of course your first discovery

01:10:54.600 --> 01:10:58.360
[Amit Varma]: of frustration was that you couldn't reach out and read these books and all that and

01:10:58.360 --> 01:11:03.040
[Amit Varma]: you've described so beautifully about how you first kind of read and you open pull this

01:11:03.040 --> 01:11:08.200
[Amit Varma]: book down you opened it and the letters were black ants and then suddenly some of those

01:11:08.200 --> 01:11:13.320
[Amit Varma]: black ants made sense to you and the first words that you remember reading therefore

01:11:13.320 --> 01:11:21.440
[Amit Varma]: are quote slowly silently now the moon walks the night in her tender shoes it was magic

01:11:21.440 --> 01:11:26.720
[Guest]: it was magic it I think some of us never forget that first moment of magic you know when you

01:11:26.720 --> 01:11:32.960
[Guest]: make the connection and whatever the thing is for some people it's cricket for some people

01:11:32.960 --> 01:11:37.040
[Guest]: it's music you know picking up their first guitar we're sitting here in a space surrounded

01:11:37.040 --> 01:11:44.600
[Guest]: by guitars and for me it was right it was not writing it was just understanding that

01:11:44.600 --> 01:11:52.000
[Guest]: all of that bewildering you know hieroglyphics the things that didn't make sense were things

01:11:52.000 --> 01:11:57.640
[Guest]: that are deeply deeply coveted and I love that so much that I famously ate a page of

01:11:57.640 --> 01:12:01.640
[Amit Varma]: the book you ate which is why your book is called the girl who ate books because you

01:12:01.640 --> 01:12:05.880
[Amit Varma]: thought to yourself if this reads so nice how well would it taste but it didn't taste

01:12:05.880 --> 01:12:12.880
[Amit Varma]: that great but it was very satisfying so my question from here is there's a sort of twofold

01:12:12.880 --> 01:12:18.560
[Amit Varma]: question and one of them is this that you have this introduction therefore into the

01:12:18.560 --> 01:12:23.520
[Amit Varma]: world of the imagination and storytelling and that's incredibly important like reading

01:12:23.520 --> 01:12:28.720
[Amit Varma]: is I take reading so seriously because we have our one life to live but when through

01:12:28.720 --> 01:12:34.040
[Amit Varma]: books you can live the lives of so many others you know through by getting inside the heads

01:12:34.040 --> 01:12:39.840
[Amit Varma]: and sort of experiencing everything that they do and and some people read and some people

01:12:39.840 --> 01:12:44.680
[Amit Varma]: don't like I'd written a column a political column but it was about reading a few years

01:12:44.680 --> 01:12:50.640
[Amit Varma]: back based on a story that a friend of Narendra Modi told me about him and her story really

01:12:50.640 --> 01:12:56.360
[Amit Varma]: was that she used to work with him in the auties in Gujarat and she was at a gathering

01:12:56.360 --> 01:13:00.980
[Amit Varma]: at his house a gathering of friends a personal gathering seven or eight people and at one

01:13:00.980 --> 01:13:05.360
[Amit Varma]: point Mr. Modi started telling this story about how his mother had fever one day and

01:13:05.360 --> 01:13:09.400
[Amit Varma]: she was ill and she was feeling very very hot and he went to turn on the fan and there

01:13:09.400 --> 01:13:15.680
[Amit Varma]: was no electricity and as he told the story he started crying right and my friend's point

01:13:15.680 --> 01:13:23.320
[Amit Varma]: was that Modi is an experiential leader in the sense that he understands the world only

01:13:23.320 --> 01:13:30.340
[Amit Varma]: through experience so therefore he has felt viscerally what electricity can mean so when

01:13:30.340 --> 01:13:35.000
[Amit Varma]: he is chief minister of Gujarat he's saying power to every village and he genuinely means

01:13:35.000 --> 01:13:41.360
[Amit Varma]: it or he has walked on roads and he understands the importance so he says build roads right

01:13:41.360 --> 01:13:47.040
[Amit Varma]: but there are some things that you cannot experience like the lives of others or like

01:13:47.040 --> 01:13:53.080
[Amit Varma]: maybe counterintuitive economic concepts like spontaneous order the positive sumness of

01:13:53.080 --> 01:13:57.740
[Amit Varma]: things and so on and so forth and when you're running a country and you cannot experience

01:13:57.740 --> 01:14:01.440
[Amit Varma]: you know all this knowledge is close to you it becomes an issue now the thing is he was

01:14:01.440 --> 01:14:05.760
[Amit Varma]: not born to privilege so it is understandable that he wasn't a reader and that he didn't

01:14:05.760 --> 01:14:12.160
[Amit Varma]: have you know books around him and all that but what one would then expect is that either

01:14:12.160 --> 01:14:17.020
[Amit Varma]: you you know begin reading whenever you can because you know you you form your picture

01:14:17.020 --> 01:14:22.080
[Amit Varma]: of the world by joining dots where do you get those dots it's mainly from reading honestly

01:14:22.080 --> 01:14:27.280
[Amit Varma]: so that's the importance of reading and even if that was not the case then rely on experts

01:14:27.280 --> 01:14:34.440
[Amit Varma]: who can cover the areas that you don't know so one I felt that reading is incredibly important

01:14:34.440 --> 01:14:40.540
[Amit Varma]: for this reason and those who shut themselves off to it are hobbling themselves and crippling

01:14:40.540 --> 01:14:45.240
[Amit Varma]: themselves in a way you know they are not allowing the best version of themselves to

01:14:45.240 --> 01:14:50.160
[Amit Varma]: ever arise in fact they're guaranteeing that a very suboptimal version of themselves is

01:14:50.160 --> 01:14:56.520
[Amit Varma]: who they will be all their lives and the other dimension across which this runs is goes back

01:14:56.520 --> 01:15:03.600
[Amit Varma]: to that question of thick desires and thin desires that the reason you know you and I

01:15:03.600 --> 01:15:09.160
[Amit Varma]: have the thick desires that we do is partly to do with because we have read so much because

01:15:09.160 --> 01:15:13.720
[Amit Varma]: our interior lives are richer for that but they have all these layers to them and a lot

01:15:13.720 --> 01:15:18.920
[Amit Varma]: of it comes from reading or a life of the imagination and so on and many people in this

01:15:18.920 --> 01:15:25.200
[Amit Varma]: desperately poor country and most of it is still desperately poor don't have that privilege

01:15:25.200 --> 01:15:29.480
[Amit Varma]: that they can read books or they have access to books and all of that and they are shut

01:15:29.480 --> 01:15:36.400
[Amit Varma]: off from this and I wonder how that affects you know those things like what people even

01:15:36.400 --> 01:15:42.120
[Amit Varma]: want what people even desire and all of that so I am rambling a little bit but just thinking

01:15:42.120 --> 01:15:47.880
[Amit Varma]: aloud about reading because if I say that you know it sounds extremely snobbish and

01:15:47.880 --> 01:15:51.640
[Amit Varma]: elitist to say that readers are a particular kind of people and non-readers are other kind

01:15:51.640 --> 01:15:56.200
[Amit Varma]: of people and you know but is this something that you think about that you and I have had

01:15:56.200 --> 01:16:00.800
[Amit Varma]: the good fortune to have been readers to whatever extent we have I've read much less than you

01:16:00.800 --> 01:16:08.520
[Amit Varma]: of course but a lot of people don't read and this has implications not just for those people

01:16:08.520 --> 01:16:14.640
[Amit Varma]: themselves but also for our society for our culture for our democracy for everything okay

01:16:14.640 --> 01:16:21.960
[Guest]: I'm going to I think we're getting to the core of what a reading life or a non-reading

01:16:21.960 --> 01:16:28.600
[Guest]: life is about so I'm going to deal with this in sections one is the points you raised about

01:16:28.600 --> 01:16:34.320
[Guest]: Mr. Modi I'm not at all sure by the way that he's not a reader he certainly is a writer

01:16:34.320 --> 01:16:42.920
[Guest]: and he's written poems for a very long period of time he's articulate and I think I remember

01:16:42.920 --> 01:16:48.320
[Guest]: from his time as Gujarat CM along with the rest of his legacy and the history of the

01:16:48.320 --> 01:16:55.360
[Guest]: riots and the engineering of those riots but one of the things that happened in the aftermath

01:16:55.360 --> 01:17:02.920
[Guest]: of the Gujarat riots when his rehabilitation was in progress was people saying but you

01:17:02.920 --> 01:17:08.640
[Guest]: know he does read he does he reads reports he reads this that and the other what we're

01:17:08.640 --> 01:17:15.440
[Guest]: speaking about here is something slightly different which is the mistaking of deep emotion

01:17:15.440 --> 01:17:23.200
[Guest]: for empathy just because a leader any leader can feel with intensity and truthfulness perhaps

01:17:23.200 --> 01:17:29.240
[Guest]: on a certain subject to feel very deeply about the plight of one section of people does not

01:17:29.240 --> 01:17:37.360
[Guest]: mean that he or she has the empathy to extend their imagination towards the goodwill and

01:17:37.360 --> 01:17:42.520
[Guest]: the well-being of everybody else in the country particularly people who are not like them

01:17:42.520 --> 01:17:49.400
[Guest]: or people who identified as the other the enemy the necessary you know person community

01:17:49.400 --> 01:17:56.240
[Guest]: against whom you pit a certain thing we don't teach political empathy and though we talk

01:17:56.240 --> 01:18:03.120
[Guest]: a lot about be kind be caring one of the reasons why writers like George Saunders or why Barack

01:18:03.120 --> 01:18:09.720
[Guest]: Obama to a certain extent in his American presidency prize something like reaching out

01:18:09.720 --> 01:18:15.720
[Guest]: and compassion is because all of these skills they interconnected and not the same compassion

01:18:15.720 --> 01:18:23.240
[Guest]: empathy kindness these are not easy things to practice particularly in leadership the

01:18:23.240 --> 01:18:30.080
[Guest]: second thing that you've touched on again with regard to Mr. Modi why doesn't he then

01:18:30.080 --> 01:18:37.360
[Guest]: pull in people who do read and who are experts on the economy or areas where the Indian project

01:18:37.360 --> 01:18:43.680
[Guest]: has palpably run into trouble if you had experts on demonetization for example you could have

01:18:43.680 --> 01:18:48.200
[Amit Varma]: spared the country a great deal of pain if you did consult experts and they told him

01:18:48.200 --> 01:18:53.680
[Guest]: not to do it Raghuram Rajan famously yeah but then you know that intolerance of an opinion

01:18:53.680 --> 01:19:00.840
[Guest]: that comes from people who are not exactly like you or have not had your background in

01:19:00.840 --> 01:19:06.960
[Guest]: the RSS that's that's a parallel problem that is a political issue let's get back to reading

01:19:06.960 --> 01:19:12.840
[Guest]: per se I think often the claims that we make for reading a very very large because we see

01:19:12.840 --> 01:19:19.120
[Guest]: the value of it okay but as a lifelong reader I've sometimes asked myself aside from the

01:19:19.120 --> 01:19:25.600
[Guest]: sheer delight of it what use is this per se everything that you say about reading I'm

01:19:25.600 --> 01:19:33.040
[Guest]: just being devil's advocate out here you can learn as much from YouTube videos okay or

01:19:33.040 --> 01:19:38.200
[Guest]: you can learn from podcasts you don't have to be a reader in order to learn skills okay

01:19:38.200 --> 01:19:44.720
[Guest]: what we found in books is to be honest about it deep and abiding delight and we've also

01:19:44.720 --> 01:19:51.880
[Guest]: found an infinitude you know of possibilities you know how many books I wrote a column about

01:19:51.880 --> 01:19:56.360
[Guest]: this for the FT which is how I know these figures I'm not just you know making them

01:19:56.360 --> 01:20:01.560
[Guest]: up but the maximum number of books that most readers are going to be able to read in a

01:20:01.560 --> 01:20:08.760
[Guest]: lifetime is 5,000 and that's if they are obsessive readers who read more than about 80 books

01:20:08.760 --> 01:20:14.200
[Guest]: a year and I remember when I came across that number I had a moment of pure panic that I

01:20:14.200 --> 01:20:19.680
[Guest]: never feel this about humans I never feel like how is how am I going to go through life

01:20:19.680 --> 01:20:25.760
[Guest]: not making all the friends I possibly could make you know but I do feel it about books

01:20:25.760 --> 01:20:31.920
[Guest]: that hunger and what I prize about books particularly is that they're one of the clearest not the

01:20:31.920 --> 01:20:38.120
[Guest]: only but they're one of the clearest windows we have to connecting with past minds everything

01:20:38.120 --> 01:20:43.120
[Guest]: else that you can learn from whether we just mentioned you know YouTube videos podcasts

01:20:43.120 --> 01:20:51.800
[Guest]: sound basically and film all of that is in by and large in the present you see so reading

01:20:51.800 --> 01:20:57.840
[Guest]: is the one thing that is so out of time music is one of the others dance is one of the others

01:20:57.840 --> 01:21:04.800
[Guest]: art yes but as an instrument for learning reading is out of time and reading challenges

01:21:04.800 --> 01:21:12.400
[Guest]: you perpetually because it keeps inviting you to inhabit other points of view not just

01:21:12.400 --> 01:21:18.880
[Guest]: listen to you know as important as that listening is it doesn't always come with identification

01:21:18.880 --> 01:21:23.600
[Guest]: when you're reading a book particularly a physical book I have nothing against reading

01:21:23.600 --> 01:21:29.880
[Guest]: audiobooks but there is a caveat to that if you're reading in a distracted space you're

01:21:29.880 --> 01:21:34.520
[Guest]: not going to be able to retain that much of the book and with an audiobook or with the

01:21:34.520 --> 01:21:40.800
[Guest]: Kindle your reading experience is often incredibly enjoyable but there's a spatial problem a

01:21:40.800 --> 01:21:46.880
[Guest]: geographical problem if you like I find that with reading on the Kindle or in audiobooks

01:21:46.880 --> 01:21:52.960
[Guest]: I never know where I am in the book does that make sense where is the physical book you

01:21:52.960 --> 01:21:56.760
[Guest]: was moving through it and you can tell whether you're at the beginning the middle or the

01:21:56.760 --> 01:22:03.680
[Guest]: end and that has an impact on the way you remember certain things from the book I do

01:22:03.680 --> 01:22:11.320
[Guest]: think that we overestimate the virtue of reading and maybe underestimate the fact that most

01:22:11.320 --> 01:22:18.120
[Guest]: of us are readers because it is sheer delight sometimes challenging sometimes unpleasant

01:22:18.120 --> 01:22:27.200
[Guest]: I just spent some time reading memoirs by a woman Shabitri Devi who was part of the

01:22:27.200 --> 01:22:33.920
[Guest]: right wing had a book blurb by Savarkar and believed firmly not just in the virtue of

01:22:33.920 --> 01:22:38.920
[Guest]: the Nazis but she believed that Hitler was alive that Jews and other people should be

01:22:38.920 --> 01:22:44.640
[Guest]: put to the sword you know and there was something cold-blooded about reading that and I think

01:22:44.640 --> 01:22:52.040
[Guest]: for a while after that I found myself you know as with Mein Kampf unable to read for

01:22:52.040 --> 01:22:58.320
[Guest]: a short while actually read for a short while because you're encountering thoughts of pure

01:22:58.320 --> 01:23:04.320
[Guest]: evil and inhumanity let's put it that way that's on label it as evil as such the thing

01:23:04.320 --> 01:23:11.740
[Guest]: that you asked about the inequality in reading in this country we've always had public libraries

01:23:11.740 --> 01:23:16.600
[Guest]: but not on a grand scale not like America what we've had is the one-room library you

01:23:16.600 --> 01:23:22.120
[Guest]: know that's how my father who grew up in the town of Cuttack in Orissa he and his brothers

01:23:22.120 --> 01:23:29.240
[Guest]: had a book hunger ignited in them in part by the fact that there were very few bookshops

01:23:29.240 --> 01:23:36.960
[Guest]: and that their access to books was so limited in a way as an adult I found that you know

01:23:36.960 --> 01:23:41.160
[Guest]: though my mother's family was surrounded by books growing up in Calcutta and all of that

01:23:41.160 --> 01:23:46.120
[Guest]: it was my father who bought books to the point where he sometimes you know drove my mother

01:23:46.120 --> 01:23:50.600
[Guest]: mad by taking the grocery money and coming back instead of with dal and rice and stuff

01:23:50.600 --> 01:23:57.480
[Guest]: like that he'd come back with figs and chocolates and time-life encyclopedias and a host of

01:23:57.480 --> 01:24:03.440
[Guest]: you know everything from Shoru Chandru to Tolkien to Toni Morrison to Garcia Marquez

01:24:03.440 --> 01:24:09.200
[Guest]: in fact a lot of my reading habits were influenced by him because he didn't believe in denying

01:24:09.200 --> 01:24:14.600
[Guest]: any of his children access to books you know he believed that if you picked up a book it

01:24:14.600 --> 01:24:19.320
[Guest]: was up to you to decide whether it was at your level or not and that was one of the

01:24:19.320 --> 01:24:26.280
[Guest]: biggest freedoms that reading gave me there was no censorship to reading you see in everything

01:24:26.280 --> 01:24:32.120
[Guest]: else particularly when you live in a country like India which has been working towards

01:24:32.120 --> 01:24:39.280
[Guest]: defining itself as a democracy but has never been as radically individualistic a society

01:24:39.280 --> 01:24:45.520
[Guest]: as America or parts of Europe and never defined itself by the freedoms of the individuals

01:24:45.520 --> 01:24:50.600
[Guest]: you know even if in its most politically free periods I don't think the freedom of the individual

01:24:50.600 --> 01:24:56.360
[Guest]: has been books are one space where you can be whatever you know you can reach for whatever

01:24:56.360 --> 01:25:01.720
[Guest]: you can be challenged outraged disgusted you can hate what you're reading you can love

01:25:01.720 --> 01:25:07.720
[Guest]: with your reading you can identify with it or not but it is a completely free space instead

01:25:07.720 --> 01:25:14.800
[Guest]: of that what we had was first the radio revolution then we had TV and then we had you know today's

01:25:14.800 --> 01:25:20.760
[Guest]: social media revolution which is to some extent also engineered for heat or for very very

01:25:20.760 --> 01:25:29.560
[Guest]: intense short compelling stories of a certain kind right what we didn't invest in as a country

01:25:29.560 --> 01:25:34.280
[Guest]: was the infrastructure that people take for granted elsewhere the infrastructure of libraries

01:25:34.280 --> 01:25:40.560
[Guest]: and bookshops and all of that you know and without that investment it's not just being

01:25:40.560 --> 01:25:48.320
[Guest]: able to afford books I grew up in Calcutta in part and it was very democratic city where

01:25:48.320 --> 01:25:52.480
[Guest]: reading was concerned it wasn't a question of whether people could afford books they

01:25:52.480 --> 01:25:58.720
[Guest]: made space in their budgets at practically every level except for the most abjectly poor

01:25:58.720 --> 01:26:05.120
[Guest]: if you were had any kind of income you would be buying books and magazines and you know

01:26:05.120 --> 01:26:11.080
[Guest]: they were cheap and you had an equality a kind of democracy as a reader you could be

01:26:11.080 --> 01:26:18.240
[Guest]: a guy on a bus sitting there reading you know Murasaki in translation and you could be sitting

01:26:18.240 --> 01:26:23.600
[Guest]: in your fancy Baliganj a red brick bungalow reading Murasaki and there'd be no difference

01:26:23.600 --> 01:26:30.200
[Guest]: between the two of you you know you both had an equally valid opinion does that make sense

01:26:30.200 --> 01:26:36.120
[Guest]: so I've often felt that we've not responded adequately to the book hunger of this country

01:26:36.120 --> 01:26:43.120
[Guest]: and that part of that is this emphasis not by you but in a lot of ways you know people

01:26:43.120 --> 01:26:49.000
[Guest]: train people to read useful things even if you're not reading textbooks but what you

01:26:49.000 --> 01:26:54.800
[Guest]: read should be informative in some way or educational or make you money right and if

01:26:54.800 --> 01:26:58.960
[Guest]: there's a reading revolution I'd like to usher in in this country it's not just the whole

01:26:58.960 --> 01:27:06.000
[Guest]: thing of more bookshops and more places to read more bookshops and let me say this I

01:27:06.000 --> 01:27:11.720
[Guest]: believe our booksellers do a wonderful job but I would also like to see bookshops and

01:27:11.720 --> 01:27:19.320
[Guest]: libraries that are beautiful and set up in all kinds of parts of the city not just in

01:27:19.320 --> 01:27:24.120
[Guest]: the affluent side of the city not just in malls you know they really should be much

01:27:24.120 --> 01:27:31.240
[Guest]: more accessible one place where we feel I'd like to see books in the hands of everybody

01:27:31.240 --> 01:27:38.200
[Guest]: because one of the things that I used to do was to work on library recommendations for

01:27:38.200 --> 01:27:43.920
[Guest]: companies that stocked libraries around Gurgaon and you know these were early versions of

01:27:43.920 --> 01:27:50.440
[Guest]: the community library that Mirdala Koshi and Michael and others run so well and these to

01:27:50.440 --> 01:27:57.280
[Guest]: sponsor specific schools and there was a point where you're stocking the library but you're

01:27:57.280 --> 01:28:03.840
[Guest]: also giving out a few of those NBT books you know the little very well-made ones or Pratham's

01:28:03.840 --> 01:28:09.640
[Guest]: books and you're making sure that every child has two or three books and one of the kids

01:28:09.640 --> 01:28:16.280
[Guest]: he was about five six years old you know just about in school he sits there and he just

01:28:16.280 --> 01:28:20.280
[Guest]: cuts off from all of us and he's just sitting there with his book and he's reading it and

01:28:20.280 --> 01:28:26.280
[Guest]: he's on each page and slowly but surely he gets to the book and then he reads it again

01:28:26.280 --> 01:28:33.600
[Guest]: and then very reluctantly he hands it back to the team member who'd given it to him and

01:28:33.600 --> 01:28:40.440
[Guest]: he said no no this is your book you know and he was like okay so he starts reading it again

01:28:40.440 --> 01:28:45.120
[Guest]: and then he tries to hand it back and then somebody realized said no this is your book

01:28:45.120 --> 01:28:52.080
[Guest]: to keep not just in school but you take it home and he was just very silent for a second

01:28:52.080 --> 01:28:56.320
[Guest]: you know he didn't say anything it was he asked several times do I get to keep this

01:28:56.320 --> 01:29:06.000
[Guest]: after a while I turned around and I see him standing there in the corridor and he's hugging

01:29:06.000 --> 01:29:14.920
[Guest]: the book to himself and he was crying because he said no one's ever given him a book before

01:29:14.920 --> 01:29:21.240
[Guest]: you know and that was how precious it was and I think from that time onwards I don't

01:29:21.240 --> 01:29:26.200
[Guest]: work in the NGO sector but if there's one thing that you get passionate about it's about

01:29:26.200 --> 01:29:32.760
[Guest]: donating books to libraries and I really respect the people who are working at community libraries

01:29:32.760 --> 01:29:37.840
[Guest]: because it's not just about handing the books out and then walking away you have to help

01:29:37.840 --> 01:29:45.960
[Guest]: people find the books that they're going to love you know and I think that whole thing

01:29:45.960 --> 01:29:50.960
[Guest]: you know the understanding that there's a dormant book love in the country that often

01:29:50.960 --> 01:29:56.800
[Guest]: doesn't come to light because there's no way to feed that book hunger the question I ask

01:29:56.800 --> 01:30:01.960
[Guest]: is really what are we depriving people of sometimes just casual pleasure you know just

01:30:01.960 --> 01:30:08.480
[Guest]: the pleasure of reading Surinder Pathak's spy stories or Ibn-e-Safi's Jasusi Duniya

01:30:08.480 --> 01:30:14.080
[Guest]: stories or something of the sort sometimes it's somebody who might find practical advice

01:30:14.080 --> 01:30:19.760
[Guest]: in a book or learn about something that later becomes a career there's so many different

01:30:19.760 --> 01:30:26.440
[Guest]: levels at which books work you know and I wish some of the money that's going into the

01:30:26.440 --> 01:30:32.160
[Guest]: current horse trading of politicians you know the cross exchanging hands in order to topple

01:30:32.160 --> 01:30:37.440
[Guest]: the state governments I wish some of that was just put towards putting a book into people's

01:30:37.440 --> 01:30:43.680
[Amit Varma]: hands it would make such a difference that's that's such a lovely story I'll respond to

01:30:43.680 --> 01:30:48.360
[Amit Varma]: three of the or rather I'll respond to what you said with three points and the first one

01:30:48.360 --> 01:30:53.880
[Amit Varma]: is like you know at one level of course it's true that you don't need to rely on books

01:30:53.880 --> 01:30:58.360
[Amit Varma]: alone for knowledge you have YouTube videos you have podcasts you have all of that but

01:30:58.360 --> 01:31:03.200
[Amit Varma]: there is something books do give you which none of the others do and and again this goes

01:31:03.200 --> 01:31:07.640
[Amit Varma]: to you know books that are not instrumental that if you want to learn something then you

01:31:07.640 --> 01:31:13.360
[Amit Varma]: read the book and you get that knowledge from there but I think fiction gives you this deeper

01:31:13.360 --> 01:31:18.440
[Amit Varma]: world of the imagination which I feel that sometimes we can take for granted even in

01:31:18.440 --> 01:31:23.880
[Amit Varma]: ourselves it's like the seen and the unseen right it's unseen there is this story of and

01:31:23.880 --> 01:31:28.000
[Amit Varma]: I'll probably say it wrong but it's a story about daddy fish and baby fish are swimming

01:31:28.000 --> 01:31:33.440
[Amit Varma]: in the water and uncle fish passes by and he asks daddy fish how's the water today and

01:31:33.440 --> 01:31:38.160
[Amit Varma]: daddy fish says great and then uncle fish goes on and then baby fish turns to daddy

01:31:38.160 --> 01:31:44.280
[Amit Varma]: fish and asks what's water you know and I think we kind of take it for granted at that

01:31:44.280 --> 01:31:48.400
[Amit Varma]: level and and not just that we and I've realized this about myself and I realized that I have

01:31:48.400 --> 01:31:55.520
[Amit Varma]: to stop doing this that I assume that if there is a certain bedrock of experiences that have

01:31:55.520 --> 01:32:01.480
[Amit Varma]: shaped me or certain cultural influences that I now take for granted that are like water

01:32:01.480 --> 01:32:06.760
[Amit Varma]: to me I assume that others share it as well but others are not everybody is swimming in

01:32:06.760 --> 01:32:12.320
[Amit Varma]: different water you know one of the reasons I like to go into the childhoods of people

01:32:12.320 --> 01:32:18.120
[Amit Varma]: of my vintage or earlier in the show so much is that 60 to 70 percent of our country is

01:32:18.120 --> 01:32:23.560
[Amit Varma]: born after liberalization you know that shared experience is not there of there being a waiting

01:32:23.560 --> 01:32:28.800
[Amit Varma]: list if you want to buy a phone of so few cars on the street as it were and all of those

01:32:28.800 --> 01:32:34.920
[Amit Varma]: things you know and I think books give you an entry into all of these worlds and they

01:32:34.920 --> 01:32:40.080
[Amit Varma]: are immersive the word you used earlier and that's not something that YouTube videos or

01:32:40.080 --> 01:32:47.080
[Amit Varma]: even podcasts such as mine will you know necessarily give people the other point almost a counterpoint

01:32:47.080 --> 01:32:54.200
[Amit Varma]: to this that I want to make is that I actually tell people that listening to audio books

01:32:54.200 --> 01:32:59.160
[Amit Varma]: is great because I think a mistake people sometimes make is that they think it's an

01:32:59.160 --> 01:33:04.040
[Amit Varma]: either or that printed books and audio books compete with each other but as I discussed

